<HEADLINE> Nepali PM: Visit to India Achieves Confidence-Building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Girija
Koirala said here Sunday that his visit to India has achieved
confidence-building, which will further strengthen Nepal-India
relations.
</P>
<P>
"I am fully satisfied with my visit," said Koirala upon his
arrival at the Kathmandu International Airport after completing
his week-long official visit to India.
</P>
<P>
"We discussed with the Indian counterparts all the issues of
Nepal-India relations and no confusion exists now in the relations
between the two countries," he added.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Koirala held official talks with his Indian
counterpart, Atal Vajpayee, and discussed the whole gamut of
bilateral relations, including the Kalapani territorial disputes,
boundary demarcation and trade issues.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers reiterated the commitment of their
governments to further strengthening the close and friendly ties
between the two countries, in a spirit of equality, mutual respect
and partnership.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that the two countries would hold regular
dialogues at various levels to continuously explore new avenues of
political, economic and scientific cooperation.
</P>
<P>
When in New Delhi, the capital of India, Koirala also called on
Indian President K. R.Narayanan and Vice President Krishan Kant
and held wide-ranging discussions with Indian Foreign Minister
Jaswant Singh on regional and international issues of mutual
concerns.
</P>
<P>
Koirala's visit to India, from July 31 to August 6, was the
first by a Nepalese prime minister since 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
