<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Adjourns Trial of Sectarian Massacre Until October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Egypt on Monday adjourned until
October 3 the trial of 96 suspects charged in the killing of 20
Christians and one Muslim early this year in a Nile Valley town in
the south of the country.
</P>
<P>
All defendants in the so-called Kosheh case will remain under
detention, a criminal court in the southern city of Suhag decided,
state-run Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
This was the second court session since the trial was first
opened on June 4. The defense attorneys argued at the court Monday
to clear the defendants of the responsibility for the events of
January, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
They also asked the court for a tape of a television news report
recorded at Kosheh just after the events and asked for the calling
of witnesses.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-eight of the defendants, all of them Muslims, face
execution if convicted on charges of premeditated murder during the
January 2 violence in Kosheh, 550 kilometers south of the capital.
</P>
<P>
The other defendants, 33 of them Coptic Christians, were being
tried on charges of attempted murder, armed robbery, destruction of
public property, illegal assembly, and illegal possession of
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Tension first erupted on December 31 in Kosheh, a mainly
Christian town of 35,000 people, following a quarrel between a
Christian merchant and a Muslim customer over a piece of cloth.
</P>
<P>
It spiraled into full-scale rioting and gunfire conflict two
days later, with market stalls and shops burned and Christians
killed. The one Muslim killed was reportedly hit by a fleeing car.
</P>
<P>
Many villages in southern Egypt have large proportions of Copts,
who account for around 9 percent of Egypt's mainly Muslim
population of 65 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
