<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Calls for Arab Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates has
called for holding an Arab summit, saying it is more urgent than
ever in view of some critical international and regional issues
needed to be discussed.
</P>
<P>
After seeing off Palestinian Leader Yasser Arafat, UAE Deputy
Prime Minister Sultan Bin Zayed Al Nahyan made the remarks in a
statement to the Emirates news agency (WAM), stressing this is the
country's official position.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Arafat's visit to the UAE was successful. The
Palestinian leader met Khalifa bin Zayed al Nahyan, Abu Dhabi crown
prince and deputy Supreme Commander of the Armed Forces, and
discussed with him the latest developments in the Mideast Peace
talks, Sultan said.
</P>
<P>
The UAE tour is part of Arafat's campaign to rally support from
Arab and Islamic countries after the failure of the Camp David
talks in the U.S..
</P>
<P>
The sticking point in the tough talks is the status of
Jerusalem. Israel proposed a shared sovereignty over Arab East
Jerusalem, captured by Israel in the 1967 Mideast War while the
Palestinians insisted on a total sovereignty over the part of the
holy city.
</P>
<P>
Sultan said that the Palestinian position reflects the Arab,
Islamic and Christian views.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that peace and stability would prevail in
the region and that Jerusalem would become the capital of Palestine
with people of all the three religions of Islam, Christianity and
Judaism free to practice their rituals in Jerusalem's holy places.
</P>
<P>
During his one-day visit, Arafat accused Israel of wanting "
Tailor-made Peace."
</P>
<P>
He also said that another U.S.-sponsored Palestinian-Israeli
summit may be held after August 14, but Israeli Prime Minister
Barak said it is "too early to discuss a new summit."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader praised UAE's President Zayed bin Sultan
Al Nahyan for his repeated calls for a unified Arab stance and his
full support to the Palestinian position on the issues of Jerusalem
and the return of Palestinian refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
