<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000 GMT, August 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- About 300 Tehran University students staged a sit-in
in front of the Majlis (parliament) building Monday, calling for
legal actions against the lawmakers who they alleged had insulted
the supreme leader, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
All these students belong to the conservative Basij -- the
volunteer force -- who pledge absolute loyalty to the supreme
leader.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Tehran Bazaar, a powerful conservative
organization of businessmen, also announced Monday that it will
organize a gathering in front of the parliament on Tuesday in
support of the supreme leader. (Iran-Protest)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey will officially launch a nationwide population
census on October 22 this year, Anatolia News Agency reported on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the State Institute of Statistics (DIE) Sefik
Yildizeli told reporters Monday that all preparations for the
population census are expected to be completed by the end of
August. The task will cost some 26 trillion Turkish Liras (about 40
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
He said a curfew will be imposed throughout the country when
necessary during the population census. (Turkey-Population Census)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Israeli soldiers on Sunday wounded a 13-year-old boy
who was hurling rocks at an observation post beside the Fatima gate
in the village of Kfar Kila and two journalists nearby, An Nahar
newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The two journalists, one from AFP and the other for Radio
Canada, were injured in abdomen and shoulder respectively while
Israeli soldiers fired back at the rock attackers. The wounded were
taken to hospital in Nabatieh. (Lebanon-Israel-Casualties)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Ahmad Zeid-Abadi, a writer working with the Tehran-
based daily Hamshahri (Citizen), was detained Monday morning under
an order issued by the press court.
</P>
<P>
Zeid-Abadi, who also worked with other periodicals, was taken
away by a group of more than 10 people who claimed they were acting
on behalf of the court dealing with offences committed by
government employees, the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA)
reported. (Iran-Writer-Arrest)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said here Monday
that it is premature to discuss a new summit with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
In reaction to earlier remarks by Palestinian National Authority
Chairman Yasser Arafat who said another summit with Israel and the
United States could take place later this month, the prime
minister's office said it was not clear whether the Palestinians
are ready for a breakthrough and there are no signs yet of
concessions on the part of the Palestinians. (Israel-Palestinians-
Summit) 
</P>
</TEXT>
