<HEADLINE> United Nations Sets up Body to Monitor Violence in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Administrative Mission in Kosovo (UNMIK) has set up a body to
monitor ethnic violence in the Yugoslav province, a spokeswoman
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement from the provincial capital of Pristina,
spokeswoman Susan Manuel said the purpose of the body would be to
compile statistics and "to define killings as political and
nonpolitical."
</P>
<P>
The would enable UNMIK to "determine what kind of incidents
are political and whether there is political trend going on," she
said.
</P>
<P>
Manuel said the new body would include representative of UNMIK
's head, Bernard Kouchner, as well as UNMIK police, the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) and the
international peacekeepers, known as KFOR.
</P>
<P>
It is essential to avoid violence during the campaign for
municipal elections, due to take place in October, she said.
</P>
<P>
The Central Election Commission would investigate complaints
of political harassment, while the police would investigate
criminal acts, she said.
</P>
<P>
Ever since UNMIK made its presence in the Serbian province in
June last year, violence broke out and non-Albanian residents were
mainly victims of the terrorist actions in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The international community has repeatedly warned UNMIK
against the trend towards independence of Kosovo, where ethnic
Albanians are fighting with Serbs for independence of the province
of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Peacekeepers Restore Calm in Sierra Leone After Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Although most of Sierra
Leone is reported as calm on Monday, there was tension reported
overnight in the nation's capital of Freetown, where one Sierra
Leone Army soldier was shot dead on Sunday night while
investigating a shooting incident, a U.N. spokesman said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, Manoel de Almeida e Silva, told a press
conference here that "U.N. peacekeepers rushed to the area of the
killing and brought the situation under control."
</P>
<P>
"Two Sierra Leone Army recruits and a civilian technician were
arrested following the incident, and a further investigation is
underway," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. peacekeepers restored the calm while its mandate
expires on Monday and the U.N. Security Council voted unanimously
last Friday to extend the mandate of the U.N. Mission in Sierra
Leone, called UNAMSIL, until September 8.
</P>
<P>
The UNAMSIL has its mandate renewed while U.N. officials
prepare recommendations to beef up the peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
Although UNAMSIL Commander Indian Major General Vijay Jetley
told reporters Thursday that he had asked the Security Council for
"many more troops" to increase from the current authorized
strength of 13,000 troops, the Council resolution did not mention
the increase.
</P>
<P>
The resolution asked U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to
provide recommendations as soon as possible for restructuring and
beefing up the force.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also gives UNAMSIL a tougher mandate to deal
with rebels violating a peace accord signed by the rebels and
government in Lome, capital of Togo, in July last year. UNAMSIL
was sent into the war-torn country to monitor the peace accord,
which was intended to end the eight-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
The resolution said attacks on UNAMSIL by the rebel
Revolutionary United Front (RUF) had "revealed serious inherent
weaknesses in the mission's structure, command and control and
resources."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. force is also due to "deter, and where necessary,
decisively counter the threat of RUF attack by responding robustly
to any hostile actions" or threat of imminent use of force, the
resolution said.
</P>
<P>
RUF, lead by Foday Sankoh, violated the peace accord by taking
more than 500 U.N. soldiers hostage and surrounding 223 others for
more than two months in the eastern part of the West African
country. Sankoh is currently in the government custody in Freetown,
capital of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The resolution said that the "widespread and serious
violations" of the Lome agreement by the RUF "constitute a
breakdown of the prior generally permissive environment based on
the agreement" and predicted on the cooperation of the parties
concerned.
</P>
<P>
Annan is expected to recommend adding several battalions,
raising the force strength to around 16,500 troops, although in a
recent report he said increasing UNAMSIL's strength would depend
on the willingness of U.N. members to provide the necessary well-
trained, well-equipped soldiers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
