<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conflict Lets Colombia 23 Bln Dls in Losses Per Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Colombian armed conflict generates
direct and indirect economic losses for around 23 billion U.S.
dollars per year, representing 30 percent of the gross domestic
product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
According to a recent research conducted by experts Luis
Londono and Rodrigo Guerrero, the war has caused 4.307 billion
dollars a year in indirect economic losses in the health sector,
and material damages amounting to 5.513 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The negative impact due to business activity reduction and the
investment withdrawal, amounts to 3.466 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, this research reveals that the Colombia's
internal conflict's indirect costs, include 5.944 billion dollars
due to consumption and labor opportunities reduction, and 3.79
billion dollars in burglary, assault, blackmail, and kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
Other figures shown as a result of the research underscore that
the war
financing costs represent five percent of the GDP, that is, some 3.
75 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the conflict resulted in the 4.1 percent fall of the
GDP in 1999 due to the "52 percent investment contraction, and
according to surveys, half this contraction can be understood due
to violence exerted on companies and houses," the research by
Londono and Guerrero noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
