<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Meeting on Ethiopia, Eritrea Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The open Security Council
meeting, originally scheduled for Tuesday on Ethiopia and Eritrea,
has been postponed later in the week, a U.N. spokesman said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Manoel de Almeida e Silva, the U.N. spokesman, told a press
conference here the postponement was made to wait for the latest
report by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who is expected to
offer detailed plan for the deployment of U.N. peacekeepers in the
Horn of Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General's next report to the Council on
Ethiopia and Eritrea, which will detail plans for a U.N. presence
there, is still being finalized and is expected to go to the
Council in the next few days," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. peacekeeping force is expected to patrol a 25-
kilometer buffer zone inside Eritrea, at which point Ethiopia's
army is to withdraw to prewar positions.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations announced two weeks ago that a senior
Finish soldier, Colonel Jukka Pollanen, had arrived in Addis Ababa,
capital of Ethiopia, to set up an office to prepare the ground for
the peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea signed the cease-fire pact in Algeria
under the auspices of the Organization of African Unity, ending
fighting in a two-year border war in which tens of thousands of
soldiers were killed.
</P>
<P>
But enmity and mistrust remain high between the Horn of Africa
neighbors. Observers here warned that skirmishes along the border
remain a possibility until the planned arrival of some 1,500 U.N.
peacekeepers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
