<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pro-Conservative Iranian Students Protest in Front of Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- About 300 Tehran University
students staged a sit-in in front of the Majlis (parliament)
building Monday, calling for legal actions against the lawmakers
who they alleged had insulted the supreme leader, Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators handed out leaflets, condemning any "
disrespect" for the supreme leader, the patron of the powerful
conservative camp, by any parliamentarians and demanded legal
punishment for such a behavior, the official Islamic Republic News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei on Sunday ordered the reformist-controlled Majlis to
cancel a scheduled debate on rewriting the press law, which sparked
a brawl and scuffling among the Majlis deputies.
</P>
<P>
After Speaker Mehdi Karrubi read out the decision to cancel the
debate at the start of Sunday's open session, some deputies
expressed strong objection, an act regarded by some others
disrespect for the supreme leader.
</P>
<P>
Several of the protesting students wore white shroud, the symbol
of sacrifice and martyrdom in Islam, saying they would not allow
the Islamic revolution to "fall into the hands of the enemy," the
IRNA report said.
</P>
<P>
All these students belong to the conservative Basij -- the
volunteer force -- who pledge absolute loyalty to the supreme
leader.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Tehran Bazaar, a powerful conservative
organization of businessmen, also announced Monday that it will
organize a gathering in front of the parliament on Tuesday in
support of the supreme leader.
</P>
<P>
The press law has become a major focus of factional struggle in
Iran. The conservative judiciary has used the restrictive law,
passed by the last, conservative-dominated Majlis before its tenure
ended, to close 20 pro-reform publications and send a number of
journalists to jail.
</P>
<P>
But the reformists, who won control of the Majlis in the
February parliamentary election, had vowed to rewrite the press law
to allow more "freedom of the press."
</P>
<P>
Their effort was dealt a deadly blow on Sunday as Khamenei
directly intervened by ordering to stop the debate in the
legislation. The tough move sets an example and is telling to the
reformists allied with President Mohammad Khatami as to who is
really in power in Iran.
</P>
<P>
The conservatives still have tight grip on most of the pivotal
state organs, including the judiciary and the military.
</P>
<P>
The ambitious reformists will find it no less difficult to push
through the reform programs advocated by President Khatami since
his took office in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Even if without direct intervention from the the supreme leader,
any bill passed by the Majlis must be endorsed by the conservative
Guardians Council before it can become law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
