<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Calls for Countering Palestinian Information Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 7 (XInhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak said on Monday that Israel should step up its "information
campaign" worldwide in light of the Palestinian efforts to
publicize their stand in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who contemporarily holds the foreign ministry portfolio,
has met with a number of officials from the ministry and rejected
former Foreign Minister David Levy's accusation that his foreign
policy is "zigzagging."
</P>
<P>
Levy resigned from the cabinet last Wednesday in protest of
Barak's alleged concessions to the Palestinians during the Camp
David summit and his "lack of sincere steps" to form a national
unity government with the opposition Likud party.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, Foreign Ministry Director General Eytan Bentsur
quit his post and was expected to receive an overseas post in a
European capital.
</P>
<P>
In an apparent concrete effort to drum up international support,
Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami, also Israel's top
negotiator with the Palestinians, is expected to arrive in Turkey
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He will brief Turkish leaders on the peace process and the
outcome of the 15-day U.S.-brokered Camp David summit, which ended
on July 25 without reaching an Israeli-Palestinian peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Next week, Ben-Ami will be joined by Transport and Tourism
Minister Amnon Lipkin-Shahak in visits to European and Muslim
countries.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister himself is also planning to visit Jordan to
meet King Abdullah II. He has met Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
who refused to pressure Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to make
concessions on the issue of Jerusalem, a sticking point which had
led to the failure of the summit.
</P>
<P>
In another development on Monday, Barak continued his effort to
rebuild his coalition government which has been left with only 12
ministers and 40 seats in the 120-member Knesset (parliament).
</P>
<P>
Barak met Knesset member Roman Bronfman to discuss the
possibility of the latter's Democratic Choice faction's joining the
coalition.
</P>
<P>
Bronfman said later that this would depend on the composition of
the coalition. He said his faction would only join a "civilian
Zionist government" that would concentrate on internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Otherwise, Bronfman said, his two-seat party would support the
government on a selective basis.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Science, Culture and Sports Matan Vilnai has said
the prime minister is still interested in bringing the ultra-
Orthodox Shas party back into the coalition, and called for
continued efforts in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Shas, the third largest grouping in the Knesset after Barak's
One Israel coalition and the Likud, bolted the government on the
eve of Barak's departure for the Camp David summit, partly to shirk
responsibility for a possible "bad agreement" that Barak might
bring back.
</P>
<P>
After the summit, Shas leadership has sent out mixed signals as
to whether it wants to return to the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Barak on Sunday named four cabinet ministers from the ruling One
Israel to be temporarily in charge of portfolio vacated by the
defected ministers. Barak said the remaining ministerial vacancies
will be filled soon although he may himself keep those of foreign
affairs and education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
