<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Protests Albania's Liaison Office in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Belgrade Monday lodged "
the strongest protest" over the establishment of the Liaison
Office of the Republic of Albania in Kosovo, a Yugoslav province,
saying that the establishment violates the U.N. Charter and the
sovereignty and territorial integrity of Yugoslavia, and that the
Office "will be abused" to further separatism and secession in the
Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
The protest, which describes the Albanian move as "unlawful
act," came in a letter to the president of the U.N. Security
Council from Vladislav Jovanovic, charge d'affaires of the
Yugoslav Mission to the United Nations. The letter is being
circulated here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Office was "characterized by the Republic of Albania as '
the establishment of diplomatic relations between Albania and
Kosovo'," Jovanovic said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that "this act of diplomatic piracy is not the first
one committed by the Republic of Albania in violation of the
principle of the Charter of the United Nations and international
law relative to respect for sovereignty and territorial integrity
of other States."
</P>
<P>
"There is no doubt that the Liaison Office of the Republic of
Albania will be abused for the furtherance of separatism,
secession of Kosovo and Metohija and the creation of Greater
Albania," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a June 10 resolution adopted last year, the Security
Council demands that all Member States should respect the
sovereignty and territorial integrity of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia and Kosovo is part of the Balkan country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
