<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Jobless Figures Affected By Birth Rate Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 7 (Xinhua) - The declining share of young people
in the workforce has lowered the sustainable rate of unemployment
in Britain, according to a research by the Bank of England.
</P>
<P>
As much as 10 percent of the drop in the jobless rate between
1984 and 1998 may have been triggered by the collapse in the birth
rate during the 1970s "baby bust", the research concludes.
</P>
<P>
This may have lowered the equilibrium rate of unemployment --
the level consistent with stable inflation -- by half a percentage
point, it suggests.
</P>
<P>
The baby bust has almost halved the number of young people in
the workforce during the past 15 years. And as younger people are
more prone to experience unemployment than old people, this has
led to a fall in the overall jobless rate.
</P>
<P>
Richard Barwell, who conducted the research, said that in 1981,
9.9 percent of the labor force were aged 16-19 and by 1994, this
had fallen to 5.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, Barwell expected that over the next few years the
youth share of employment will increase slightly while the number
of people aged 25-34 will decline sharply as the "baby bust"
generation grows older. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
