<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Motoring In Britain Costs More Than Mortgage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Motorists in Britain spend more
running a car than paying mortgage, according to the official
figures released Monday.
</P>
<P>
Diaries kept by more than 11,000 households show the cost of
motoring has for the first time outstripped the cost of
accommodation and food.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated car owners aged under 50 now spend up to a
fifth of their income on buying and running a car when
depreciation is included.
</P>
<P>
The Family Expenditure Survey reveals that the weekly price of
keeping a car has risen to more than 71 pounds since figures were
last published in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Food and non-alcoholic drink now account for 66 pounds of the
average family's weekly budget and rent or mortgage repayments
make up 67 pounds.
</P>
<P>
It is generally acknowledged that the figures compiled by the
Office for National Statistics, were further evidence that drivers
were being unfairly penalized.
</P>
<P>
In the past 10 years fuel costs have doubled but an Auto
Association spokesman said: "It is not just petrol, insurance has
rocketed and car prices are dearer in Britain than anywhere else
in Europe."
</P>
<P>
"The cost of running a car has far outstripped inflation. For
some people it is now becoming untenable to run a car," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
