<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Earns Another 353 Million U.S. Dollars in U.N. "Oil-for-Food Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Iraq exported some 353
million U.S. dollars worth of oil last week, the latest figures
from the United Nations Office of Iraq Program said on Monday
</P>
<P>
The Office, which administers the U.N. humanitarian "oil-for-
food" program, reported that for the week to August 4, Iraq
exported 14.9 million barrels of oil under the program.
</P>
<P>
The Office said since the beginning of Phase Eight on June 9,
2000, Iraq has now exported 106.8 million barrels for revenue
estimated around 2560 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the last week, the United Nations Security Council Sanctions
Committee approved a further seven contracts for the export of
Iraq oil, bringing the total of approved contracts to 92 for a
volume of 368.38 million barrels, the Office added.
</P>
<P>
Under the Security Council resolution establishing the "oil-for-
food program," 66 percent of earning goes to fund the country's
humanitarian needs and 30 percent is directed to the Compensation
Commission, which pays claims arising from Iraq's 1990 invasion of
Kuwait. The remainder goes to pay the costs of the U.N. Monitoring,
Verification and Inspection Commission and U.N. operational costs.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions against Iraq cannot be lifted until the United
Nations clarifies that Iraq has destroyed all its weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. arm inspectors have been away from Iraq since the U.S.
-led military air strikes against the country in December 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
