<HEADLINE> Greece Sets Up Hotlines for Information on Terrorists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Greece has set up two hotlines for
information on terrorists as part of its efforts to deal with the
increasingly terrorist acts in the country.
</P>
<P>
The hotlines, the first of its kind in Greece, were linked
with Greece's anti-terrorist service and would be staffed on a 24-
hour basis, the semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
No caller ID or recording machine would be placed on the two
lines and that conversation would be strictly confidential.
</P>
<P>
In the past 26 years, Greece's "November 17" terrorist group
has killed more than 20 people, including Britain's defense
attache in Greece Stephen Saunders, who was shot dead in early
June.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the Greek police are closely cooperating with
Britain's Scotland Yard in a bid to bring those responsible for
the killing to justice.
</P>
<P>
Seeking to grant the police and judiciary wider powers in
dealing with terrorism cases, the Greek government is expected to
submit a counter-terrorism bill to the parliament this month.
</P>
<P>
The bill calls for the abolishment of measures construed as
protecting terrorism suspects while it will also allow for house
searches.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Greece's Justice Minister Michalis Stathopoulos will
visit the U.S. to sign a police cooperation protocol between the
two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
