<HEADLINE> Slight of Duty in Dutroux's Video Tapes: Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A slight of duty was reported
Monday on the part of investigators into the Marc Dutroux case as
some confiscated video tapes had never been viewed to help
pinpoint the child abuser and killer much earlier.
</P>
<P>
Dutroux is described by local people as the most notorious
child abuser and killer in Belgium and his arrest in 1996 and his
attempt to escape from police in 1998 twice caused sensation
around the country.
</P>
<P>
La Derniere Heure newspaper quoted the country's special
committee P (police of polices) as saying that some video tapes
confiscated from Dutroux's house at Marcinelle in December 1995
was never viewed by the investigators.
</P>
<P>
But the content of the video tapes was not revealed.
</P>
<P>
Dutroux was arrested in 1994 and released not long after. He
was arrested in August 1996 charged with abusing, raping and
killing two little girls.
</P>
<P>
Two more girls were later found dead within the premises of his
house and local people have been accusing the police of slight of
duty for otherwise the girls could have been saved. Autopsy
results showed that the two girls died of starvation after Dutroux
had been arrested.
</P>
<P>
Some 300,000 people from around Europe gathered in Brussels to
protest against the police dysfunction in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
Dutroux then stirred up another sensation when he broke loose
from two accompanying gendarmerie just prior to a pre-trial
hearing at Neufchateau in southeastern Belgium in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of police and gendarmerie had to be mobilized from
Belgium, Luxembourg, Germany and the Netherlands in the ensuing
manhunt that took more three hours to catch him again.
</P>
<P>
Two Belgian cabinet ministers had to resign to take the
responsibility of this attempted escape from police and
gendarmerie. The country is now under pressure for reforms on its
justice and law enforcement systems.
</P>
<P>
It was not until February last year when people viewed one of
the confiscated tapes which was taken away by a gendarme.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted the committee P as labeling the police
dysfunction as "a lack of rigor and of professionalism". But the
committee did not say whether an earlier viewing of the
confiscated video tapes could have led to early arrest of Dutroux.
</P>
<P>
The committee P reported on Monday its finding on the police
dysfunction to the general prosecutor in Liege and is expected to
report to the Belgian parliament soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
