<HEADLINE> Gore Names Senator Lieberman as Running Mate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Washington, August 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Democratic presidential
candidate Monday named Connecticut Senator Joseph Lieberman as his
running mate and Lieberman accepted the offer.
</P>
<P>
Gore made the offer in a telephone call to Lieberman on Monday,
making the Senator become the first Jewish vice-presidential
candidate in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
"It is a special honor to be asked to run for vice-president
with a man I deeply believe in, Al Gore, and who I think is ready
to be a great president," Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
Lieberman, 58, was picked up after beating five other finalists,
Indiana Senator Evan Bayh of Indiana, North Carolina Senator John
Edwards, Massachusetts Senator John Kerry, House Minority Leader
Dick Gephardt and New Hampshire Governor Jeanne Shaheen.
</P>
<P>
Vice-President Gore and his running mate are expected to appear
together in Nashville of Tennessee State for a formal announcement
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew, is also known as the first Democrat
publicly to criticize President Bill Clinton for the Monica
Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
By selecting a political moderate like Lieberman, Gore is
trying to reach out to both independents and Republicans and
distance himself from Clinton's controversies, observers here said.
</P>
<P>
Gore trailed Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush
by 17 points in the CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll released Sunday. The
poll was taken just after the Republican National Convention
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Lieberman, who was first elected to the Senate in 1988 and got
re-elected in 1994, bills himself as pro-business, pro-environment
and pro-defense. He has served as chairman of the Democratic
Leadership Council in the past five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
