<HEADLINE> Russia's Military Pullout to Avail Ties With Georgia: Shevardnadze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Russian troops' withdrawal
from Georgia will help improve the relations between the two
countries, not leading to their degradation, Georgian President
Eduard Shevardnadze told an interview with the national radio
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Russia's pulling out its technical weapons and gradually
removing its military bases from Georgia "don't mean the
complication and deterioration of the traditionally friendly
relations between the two countries," the Interfax news agency
quoted Shevardnadze as saying in the interview in Tbilisi, capital
of the former soviet republic.
</P>
<P>
The military withdrawal from Georgia will do no harm to Russia'
s national security, but accelerate the improvement of the
relationship between the two states and strengthen their mutual
trust in each other, stressed the president.
</P>
<P>
He noted that other member nations of the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS) do not have Russian military bases on
their soil but maintain normal relations with Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Georgian-Russian ties should be established and develop on the
basis of equality, mutual benefit and respecting both nations'
interests, Shevardnadze added.
</P>
<P>
Under the treaty on conventional armed forces in Europe and
bilateral agreements reached between Georgia and Russia, Moscow
started military withdrawal from Georgia since the beginning of
this month. By the end of this year, Russian will pull out 244
pieces of technical weapons from the republic.
</P>
<P>
The Russian military bases in the towns of Vaziani and Gudauta
in Georgia's conflicting region of Abkhazia are also being
withdrawn in line with an understanding reached at the OSCE (the
Organization of Security and Cooperation for Europe) summit held
in the Turkish port-city of Istanbul earlier this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
