<HEADLINE> Israeli Rabbinate Studies Synagogue on Temple Mount </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Chief Rabbinate Council
Monday discussed a proposal on building a synagogue on Temple Mount
and set up a committee which would review the restrictions of the
Jewish law concerning entry by Jews into the holy area.
</P>
<P>
Despite earlier reports that the subject would not be discussed
out of political considerations, the council held a preliminary
debate on the proposal by Rabbi Shear-Yeshuv Cohen, chief rabbi of
the northern coastal city of Haifa.
</P>
<P>
Rabbi Cohen presented historical findings regarding the ever
existence of a synagogue on the Temple Mount and material evidence
from research studies by former Chief Rabbi Shlomo Goren. Temple is
the most sacred place in Judaism and also home to Islamic shrines.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the majority of Israel's senior rabbis, the late Rabbi
Goren favored permitting Jews to visit the Temple Mount, located in
the Old City in East Jerusalem that the Palestinians are striving
to make the capital of their future state.
</P>
<P>
Rabbi Cohen said there are enough opinions and findings to
detail the area where the Jews are permitted to enter. Therefore,
the project to establish a synagogue on the Temple Mount should
proceed.
</P>
<P>
But so far the council has not changed the rabbinical ruling
that Jews must not enter the Temple Mount for fear of treading on
holy ground.
</P>
<P>
A few weeks after the 1967 Middle East War in which Israel
seized East Jerusalem, 56 of Israel's most important rabbis issued
a warning against Jews' entering "the entire area of the Temple
Mount," lest they violate the "strict prohibition against
desecrating the purity of the temple site."
</P>
<P>
Mufti of Jerusalem Ekrima Sa'id Sabri warned Sunday that "if the
Al-Aqsa Mosque (Islam's third holiest shrine) is harmed, not only
the Muslims here but the Muslims all over the world will not sit
idly by."
</P>
<P>
The status of Jerusalem, particularly sovereignty over the
Temple Mount, is the toughest issue in Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks, which aim to a peace deal by September.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Minister for Jerusalem Affairs Faisal Husseini has
urged the Israelis to stop attempts to build a synagogue at the
contentious holy area and said the project could be an obstacle to
peace.
</P>
<P>
The minister, in a commentary published on International Herald
Tribune Monday, also said that the Palestinians recognize the
interests of the Jewish people in Jerusalem and seek to share the
Holy City with the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
He said the city is already divided and compromise on it by both
sides is possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
