<HEADLINE> Singapore Unions Leader: Cooperate to Prevent Structural Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Singapore labor unions leader
has called for tripartite cooperation among the government, unions
and employers in the country's efforts to prevent the increasing
structural unemployment.
</P>
<P>
In his National Day message to unions and employers Monday, Lim
Boon Heng, Secretary-General of the National Trade Unions
Congress and Minister without Portfolio, said Singapore can keep
structural unemployment from taking root only if the government,
unions and employers work as a team.
</P>
<P>
He also said that there is a need to attract more investments
so that Singapore can have more and better jobs.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that the key lies with each and everyone who seizes
the opportunity to upgrade skills, he urged workers to assume
individual responsibility and save part of their income for
retraining where necessary.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Minister for Manpower Lee Boon Yang revealed Sunday
that retrenchments hit 7,700 in Singapore in the first half of
this year, 1,000 more than the 6,700 retrenchments seen in the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
He also said that June's unemployment rate reached 3.5 percent,
a figure significantly higher than the pre-crisis unemployment
rate of less than 2 percent and also up from the rate of 3.4
percent for the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the rise of unemployment mainly to increasing
retrenchments in the manufacturing sector which was most severely
affected by the cycle of upgrading and restructuring.
</P>
<P>
Older and lower skilled workers were retrenched by a
restructuring economy and they were unable to take up newly-
created jobs because of lack of needed skills, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that his government hopes to increase the skilled
workers to 65 percent of the whole workforce from the current 34
percent over the next 15 years and reduce the semi-skilled and
unskilled workers to 20 percent and 15 percent respectively from
the present-day 28 percent and the 38 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
