<HEADLINE> Personal Computers Sales Surge in Czech Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, August 7 (Xinhua) -- More and more Czechs are buying
personal computers and every four Czech citizens own a PC for
household use, reflecting an Internet boom among consumers, the
Czech newspaper "Dnes" (Today) reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Since last autumn, a growing appetite to use e-mail and surf
the Internet has boosted sales of PCs, the newspaper said.
According to latest statistics, 24.9 percent of the households in
the Czech Republic have PCs, compared with 14.7 percent last year
and the figure is among the highest in the central-eastern
European countries.
</P>
<P>
About 388,000 Czechs, or 4.7 percent of the country's
population, now frequently access the Internet, an rise of 3.2
percent recorded at the beginning of last year.
</P>
<P>
To encourage more people to buy household PCs, the Czech
parliament recently passed a bill, which would allow computer
industry firms to lower PC prices by up to 9,000 Korunas (243 U.S.
dollars) each. 
</P>
</TEXT>
