<HEADLINE> Gore Selects Lieberman as Running Mate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice President Al Gore
has selected Connecticut Senator Joseph Lieberman as his running
mate, the AP reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Gore will call Lieberman later Monday to inform him of the
decision and the two will appear together in Nashville of
Tennessee State for a formal announcement Tuesday, the report
quoted Democratic sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Gore made the decision after consulting with his top advisors,
including former Secretary of State Warren Christopher, who headed
up his search process, his brother-in-law Frank Hunger, his wife
Tipper and campaign chairman Bill Daley.
</P>
<P>
Lieberman, 58, will be the first Jewish vice presidential
candidate in American history.
</P>
<P>
Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew, is also known as the first Democrat
publicly to criticize President Bill Clinton for the Monica
Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
Gore selected Lieberman from a short list of possible
candidates, including Massachusetts Senator John Kerry, North
Carolina Senator John Edwards, Indiana Senator Evan Bayh, House
Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt and New Hampshire Governor Geanne
Shaheen.
</P>
<P>
By selecting a political moderate like Lieberman, Gore is
trying to reach out to both independents and even Republicans and
distance himself from Clinton's controversies, observers here said.
</P>
<P>
Lieberman, who was first elected to the Senate in 1988 and got
re-elected in 1994, bills himself as pro-business, pro-environment
and pro-defense. He has served the past five years as chairman of
the Democratic Leadership Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
