<HEADLINE> All-Woman Jumpers Make Olympic History in Equestrain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- History was made on Sunday
when an all-woman show-jumping equestrain team earned the right to
represent the United States in the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Never before in the male-dominated sport has an all-woman team
competed for any country in the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Margie Goldstein-Engle, 42, qualified in the top spot at the
Del Mar Horsepark, and will lead her women compatriots Nona Garson,
Laura Kraut and Lauren Hough into history.
</P>
<P>
"There's a lot more women riders here," Goldstein-Engle said, "
In Europe it's the opposite. There will probably be more women on
our team than all the others put together."
</P>
<P>
Goldstein-Engle, Garson and Kraut led the field by so much
going into the final round, they didn't even have to jump,
although Goldstein-Engle brought her Perin, a 10-year-old
Westphalian gelding out to give him a shot at the liverpool, a
jump he has never attempted.
</P>
<P>
Kraut and Garson chose not to jump the final round.
</P>
<P>
For Hough, however, the final round was crucial as she trailed
Todd Minikus by 0.25 faults, and was tied with Nicole Shahinian-
Simpson.
</P>
<P>
After Shahinian-Simpson committed 12 faults, knocking her out
of contention, Minikus recorded a round of eight, taking over the
fourth and final qualifying spot.
</P>
<P>
Hough, an Olympic team gold medalist and individual silver
medalist in the 1984 Games, came next and she dazzled the crowd
with perfection through the first eight jumps before just brushing
No. 9 an oxer for her only fault.
</P>
<P>
"It hasn't hit me yet," said Hugh, 23, "I'm in shock, but I
didn't want to think about it. I knew coming down the last line I'
d make it and I just wanted to get it over with." 
</P>
</TEXT>
