<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abu Sayyaf Gained Money From Kidnapping: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A ranking Philippine official said
Monday that Abu Sayyaf kidnappers have obtained some 245 million
pesos(6.13 million U.S. dollars) paid by foreign countries for the
release of eight hostages including six Malaysians and two Germans.
</P>
<P>
Armed Forces of the Philippines (AFP) chief of staff Angelo
Reyes admitted during Monday's cabinet meeting that the virtual
ransom payments under the name of "board and lodging" fee were
handed over in backdoor negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Reyes said the money is now being used to acquire rebel
firearms and ammunition.
</P>
<P>
Other government officials, including chief hostage crisis
negotiator Secretary Robert Aventajado downplayed Reyes' admission
during the cabinet meeting, stressing that the Philippine
government has stood by its no-ransom policy.
</P>
<P>
Press secretary Ricardo Puno, for his part, supported
Aventajado's claim that the government has had nothing to do with
supposed payments to the Abu Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
"We don't think anything about the Abu Sayaf's supposedly
receiving ransom money. The chief negotiator as we heard is still
maintaining his policy of no ransom and he will continue to talk
to them on that basis," Puno said.
</P>
<P>
However, Puno also said that the government cannot control the
flow of money if there are groups willing to pay ransoms to the
kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
The press secretary also admitted that the Abu Sayyaf has
acquired more firearms and ammunition but stressed that the AFP is
now in addressing the situation.
</P>
<P>
Puno said the government is still confident that hostage
release negotiation would resume, and that the remaining 30
hostages, including 13 Filipino evangelists led by Wilde Almeda
will be released soon.
</P>
<P>
Among the other hostages are five French nationals including
three journalists, three Malaysians, two Germans, two Finnish
nationals, a South African couple, two Filipinos, and one Lebanese.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
