<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dialogue on Kashmir Cannot Exclude Pakistan: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Monday insisted that
any dialogue aimed at a final solution to the long-standing
Kashmir dispute cannot exclude it.
</P>
<P>
"A peaceful negotiated settlement of the Kashmir dispute has to
be through a dialogue between India and Pakistan in which
participation of Kashmiri leaders is indisputable," said Foreign
Office spokesman Riaz Muhammad Khan at a press briefing here.
</P>
<P>
He said the United Nations Security Council resolutions on
Kashmir have recognized Pakistan and India as the two principal
parties to the dispute.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot see a dispute be solved outside the perimeter
identified by U.N resolutions," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Khan, the first of all conditions for a just
settlement of the Kashmir dispute is India's termination of all
oppression against the Kashmiri people and the Kashmiri freedom
struggle."
</P>
<P>
He urged India to stop "massive human rights violations" in
Kashmir and "respond positively to the international community's
call for a dialogue with Pakistan."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the recent communication between the Indian
government and Hizbul Mujahideen, a major Muslim militant group in
India-controlled Kashmir, Khan said that put to test India's
sincerity to a negotiated, peaceful settlement of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The development ought to lead up to a peaceful solution of the
dispute in accordance with international norms, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hizbul Mujahideen, which announced unilateral ceasefire late
last month, has been engaged in talks with the Indian government.
However, the group also insisted on Pakistan's involvement in a
tripartite dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The group has asked India to respond "positively" to its
requirement otherwise it would resume fighting against Indian
forces in the India-controlled part of Kashmir. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
