<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi Interior Minister Nayef Bin Abdul-Aziz has
issued a decree, banning foreigners under 40 years old from working
in the fields of selling gold, garments and women clothings.
</P>
<P>
The governors of districts and quarters concerned were
instructed by the minister to form work teams to oversee the
implementation of the edict, together with the closure of offending
shops.
</P>
<P>
Gold, cloth and women garment shops make up 60-70 percent of the
total department stores in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The number of foreign workers in Saudi Arabia amounts to 6-7
million, mostly working in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- Sudanese Finance Minister Mohammed Kheir el-Zobair
said his country's foreign debts has reached 20 billion U.S.
dollars, including 1.6 billion dollars to the International
Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
A special department in charge of foreign debts issues has been
established at the ministry.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum of understanding was also concluded in March 1999
for kicking off an economic reform drive covering the period from
1999 to 2001 under IMF surveillance.
</P>
<P>
Sudan will pursue paying off its debts including the 1.6 billion
US dollar debt to the IMF.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey will undertake a modernization project on the
78-kilometer railway between Aliaga-Cumaovasi in the southwestern
Izmir province in September.
</P>
<P>
A senior State Railways (TCDD) official said on Monday that the
modernization project will take 26 months and cost 200 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Spanish companies will carry out the electrification renovation
while Japanese companies will undertake signalization renovation.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish Tourism Minister Erkan Mumcu said on Sunday
that figures of the first seven months of this year showed that the
sector could overfulfil its target of attracting 10 million
tourists in 2000.
</P>
<P>
A total of 5.5 million tourists have visited the country by the
end of July.
</P>
<P>
By virtue of an extensive public relations project that is to be
carried out, the sector expects to bring in some 20 billion dollars
in tourist revenue next year, he said. 
</P>
