<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Reports High Crime Solution Efficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine National Police (
PNP) recorded a 93.43 percent crime solution efficiency during the
first semester of the year, Edgardo Aglipay, chief of the PNP-
National Capital Region, reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Aglipay, along with other top PNP officials, reported about the
peace and order situation in the country during the cabinet
meeting presided over by President Joseph Estrada at the
Presidential Palae.
</P>
<P>
In the same meeting, Reynaldo Wycoco, PNP deputy chief for
administration, also cited the 39 percent drop in heinous crimes
committed, as well as the decline of 20 percent in kidnap-for-
ransom cases.
</P>
<P>
He said the figure on kidnapping incidents could have lowered,
had it not been for the kidnap-for-ransom activities of the
terrorist Abu Sayyaf Group in the southern province of Sulu.
</P>
<P>
Wycoco said in the National Capital Region (NCR), no kidnapping
incident was recorded between June and July this year, an
indication that the campaign against kidnap syndicates has been
successful.
</P>
<P>
However, Wycoco admitted that the rate of kidnapping in the
country could still go up, as the Abu Sayyaf prepares to abduct
more victims, in an effort to raise more funds to beef up its
defense capability and sustain its fight against the government.
</P>
<P>
Armed forces officials admitted that the government intends to
go all out against the Abu Sayyaf, as soon as the remaining 29
Filipino and foreign hostages are released.
</P>
<P>
Wycoco said this reality may be the reason the Abu Sayyaf would
want to drag the negotiations for the release of its hostages, in
an effort to delay any military action against them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
