<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Exports to U.S. to Increase by 6 Percent This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Thai exports to the United States
are expected to grow by 6 percent this year, thanks to continued
growth in the U.S. economy, the Thai News Agency (TNA) said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Inspector attached to the Ministry of Commerce Orachit
Singkalavanich was quoted as saying that Thai exports to the U.S.
market steadily increased in the first six months of this year,
reaching 6.76 billion U.S. dollars or a 17.3 percent year-on-year
increase; while imports rose 3.4 percent to 3.40 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The trend led to an estimation that total Thai exports to the U.
S. market would reach 15.18 billion dollars at the end of this
year, an increase of 6.50 percent from the previous year, she said.
</P>
<P>
Key Thai exports to the U.S. this year include IC circuits,
computer chips, frozen seafood, rubber gloves, natural rubber
products, furniture and cement.
</P>
<P>
She cautioned, however, that the direction of U.S. imports was
changing, with countries in South and Central America, rather than
Asian countries, emerging as key sources, particularly textile and
garment products, and footwares.
</P>
<P>
Neighboring countries, namely Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar, and
Vietnam are also becoming key rivals for Thai exporters, she noted.
</P>
<P>
Orachit, therefore, suggested that Thai manufacturers and
exporters adjust their business strategies and planning to meet
the new challenges, and to maintain their competitiveness in the
long-run. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Official Asks More Money for Protected Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Environment and
Natural Resources Secretary Antonio Cerilles stressed Monday that
there is a need for more public investment in the management and
conservation of the country's protected areas.
</P>
<P>
He said in a statement that these protected areas "represent
the last frontier of our flora and fauna as well as our last great
natural areas of intrinsic, inspirational and recreational values.
"
</P>
<P>
Cerilles said that the conservation of the country's
biodiversity, the management of its ecosystem, especially in the
protected areas, are expected to face more difficulties unless
more funds will be pumped into the proposed 2001 budget.
</P>
<P>
To effectively conserve biodiversity through the country's
systems of more than 100 protected areas, he proposed at least 600
million pesos (15 million U.S. dollars) be given to the management
of these areas.
</P>
<P>
"The money being spent for protected areas and biodivesity
conservation should not be viewed by Congress as a burden or
unrecoverable expense. Instead, it should be seen as an investment
similar to that in public education or health," Cerilles said.
</P>
<P>
Cerilles said that protected areas provide safeguards for
ecosystems essential in maintaining life-support systems; for
culturally important landscapes, historic monuments and other
heritage sites; and for sustainable use of wild resources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
