<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian Is To Improve Its Railway System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Railway has
recently approved the building of two railways to promote this
opening-front Fujian Province's economy.
</P>
<P>
Fujian, in southeast China, now has only three railways,
totalling 1200 km, or 0.35 km for every 10 thousand people, much
lower than that of national standard of 0.54 km.
</P>
<P>
The 277-km Wenfu Railway, which connects the neigboring
Zhejiang Province, one of the two and costing 6.2 billion yuan (
747 million US dollars), is to be constructed in early 2002. The
325-km Ganglong Railway, which connects Jiangxi Province, the
other and costing 8 billion yuan (964 million US dollars), is to
be completed at the end of 2004, according to a local railway
official.
</P>
<P>
The completion of the two new railways will fundamentally
change Fujian's backward state in railway transport, experts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
