<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Neighborhood Committee in Transformation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Kong Ruoxue, a 22-year-old
college graduate, has become a hot topic of conversation recently
among residents of Chaoyang District in this capital city of Jilin
Province, northeast China.
</P>
<P>
Kong is Jilin's first college graduate who works with
neighborhood or residents' committee.
</P>
<P>
The neighborhood committee is a self-governed organization in
urban China. There are more than 117,000 such committees
nationwide, which play an important role in China's political,
economic, cultural and social affairs as well as in people's daily
life.
</P>
<P>
For decades, less-educated or retired women are the dominant
staff in residents' committees. Kong's participation through
public election brings new vitality to this traditional grassroots
management unit in China.
</P>
<P>
Majoring in international trade, Kong holds a firm belief to
make full use of her knowledge, such as the consumption psychology,
statistics and marketing, to serve the people in her community.
</P>
<P>
"Kong's recent creation of a software program on managing the
local population has saved us from door-to-door investigations,"
said Guo Zhimin, who has worked in the same committee for 15 years.
"We have never imagined that we now use computer software to the
neighborhood committee."
</P>
<P>
More educated young people like Kong are showing great interest
in the community service all over China. Open election by
residents has replaced appointment in the formation of the
neighborhood committee in recent years. Beijing, Shanghai, Tianjin,
and many other major cities are also trying to improve the
community service system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
