<HEADLINE> Chinese T-Bond Trading Up Broadly Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- China's T-bond market rose with
expanded trade volume as some investors gradually move money into
fixed income securities on concerns that the stock market may have
corrections soon at the present high level.
</P>
<P>
All the six current bonds advanced with gains ranging from 0.02
percent to 0.27 percent. Transaction value totaled 1.91 billion
yuan, 393 million yuan more than last Friday, according to Homeway,
a leading online financial information provider.
</P>
<P>
The 10-year floating-rate 010004 jumped 0.27 percent to reach
record high of 103.77 yuan, driving the yield down 0.03 percentage
points to 2.47 percent.
</P>
<P>
Bond 000696 (11.83 percent, due 2006) picked up 0.16 percent to
143.65 yuan, while bond 009704 (9.8 percent, due 2007) rose 0.10
percent. Yields on the two bonds closed at 3.73 percent and 3.86
percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
China's repo market was upbeat today. The combined turnover of
three-day, seven-day, 14-day and 28-day repo transactions expanded
by 3.98 billion to 8.74 billion yuan. Meanwhile, the close price
of the three-day transaction ended at 2.85 percent, tripling that
on last Friday. 
</P>
