<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Minister Due in Turkey to Push Mideast Peace Forward </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Public Security Minister
Shlomo Ben-Ami will visit Turkey this weekend to update Turkish
leaders with the issues taken up at last month's Camp David peace
summit, Anatolia News Agency reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials told the agency that Ben-Ami will not request
anything from Turkey, adding Israel is "satisfied" with Turkey's
statements issued after the Camp David summit and after Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat's visit to Ankara last week.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who arrived here last Saturday to brief Turkish leaders
on the latest developments of the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks,
tried to rally support from Ankara for his declaration of an
independent Palestinian state on September 13 with or without a
peace agreement with Israel.
</P>
<P>
He also urged Turkey to play a more active role in the Middle
East peace process, especially in the talks with Israel over the
fate of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Ottoman Turks ruled Jerusalem, as well as the rest of the
Middle East, for 400 years until early 20th century.
</P>
<P>
Turkish leaders have assured during meetings with Israeli
officials that they will stress Ankara's sensitivity over the
Jerusalem issue and urge the Israeli government to review its
policies over the holy sites in the city.
</P>
<P>
However, they voiced no clear support for Arafat's decision to
unilaterally declare a Palestinian state. During Saturday's talks,
Turkish leaders advised Arafat to be moderate, saying his
unilateral move will bring about confusion and chaos to the region
and should be thought over.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials said Turkey is in favor of maintaining
negotiations and refraining from unilateral moves, an attitude in
parallel with a tripartite declaration issued at the end of the
Camp David summit which failed to produce any agreement.
</P>
<P>
They told the agency that they hope Ankara will recommend Arafat
to keep from taking unilateral actions, adding Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak has sent a letter to his Turkish counterpart
Bulent Ecevit to this end.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Israeli government does not want
Turkey's direct intervention in the Middle East peace process, but
appreciates Ankara's moderate advice to Arafat while Arab countries
are reluctant to pressure Arafat to make concessions in the peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said Turkey is trying to pursue a balanced position
between its Muslim brother Palestine and its Mideast ally Israel.
</P>
<P>
When the Middle East peace process was launched in Madrid,
Spain, in 1991, Turkey allowed the Palestine Liberation
Organization (PLO) Office in Ankara to be turned into an embassy.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Turkey has formed close military, political
and economic ties with Israel in order to contain their common
rivals Syria and Iran in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Turkey was one of the first Muslim countries to recognize Israel
in 1948. Ankara lowered its level of diplomatic representation to
charge d'affaires in Tel Aviv in 1981 when Israel declared
Jerusalem as its "eternal" capital. It also closed its consulate-
general in Arab East Jerusalem as well.
</P>
<P>
And Turkey reciprocally upgraded its diplomatic relations with
Israel to the level of ambassador in 1991 when it turned the PLO
Office in Ankara into an embassy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0121 </DOCNO>
