<HEADLINE> Philippines to Reform Revenue Collection System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
reassured the public Monday that it continues to introduce reforms
in the revenue collection system so that the government can lessen
its need to borrow funds for its priority projects.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said in a press statement
that this effort may take years, as it requires a computerized
database and a professional collection staff.
</P>
<P>
"We have to overhaul our revenue collection system. We cannot
do that in one to two years. We have to put in a computerized
system, professionalize the revenue collection agencies," Zamora
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that while President Joseph Estrada is bent on
introducing reforms to the revenue collection system, he has been
in office for barely two years.
</P>
<P>
Some economists have indicated that the Philippine economy
cannot grow much because of perceived flaws in the revenue
collection system.
</P>
<P>
Zamora, however, said introducing changes in the system is not
an easy job, as many of the problem have deep roots.
</P>
<P>
On July 24, Estrada stressed the need for reforms when he
submitted to Congress the government's proposed budget of 725
billion pesos (18.1 billion U.S. dollars) for fiscal year 2001.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said the proposed budget is anchored on a spending
approach that is "strategic and reforms-driven," and was drafted
with the country's strengths and weaknesses in mind. 
</P>
</TEXT>
