<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bilingual People Increase among China's Ethnic Minorities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The number of bilingual people,
who have mastered both Chinese and languages of other ethnic
minorities, is increasing steadily.
</P>
<P>
According to today's Liberation Army Daily, it is estimated
that 68 million Chinese use ethnic minority languages, accounting
for about 60 percent of the ethnic minority in the country.
Except for the Hui and Manchu nationalities, which adopted
mandarin Chinese, all ethnic minorities in China have their own
languages, which total more than 80.
</P>
<P>
However, before the founding of New China in 1949, the majority
of the ethnic minorities did not have their own languages.
</P>
<P>
In the 1950s, the Chinese government began to help the ethnic
minorities invent and improve their languages and great success
has been achieved.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, 83 newspapers and 184 magazines have been
published in 17 ethnic languages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> City on "Silk Road" Eyes Developing Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A 2,600-year-old city near the
world famous "Silk Road" will be revived by taking advantage of
its tourism potential, but transportation seems to be a major
obstacle toward achieving such a goal.
</P>
<P>
"As a city of rich historical and cultural resources, Tianshui
will spare no effort to tap into its tourism potential," said Vice-
Mayor Sun Weixi.
</P>
<P>
Located in the eastern part of China's northwest province of
Gansu, Tianshui has been known as the starting point of the "Silk
Road" and one of the cradles of the Chinese nation. It has over
245 sites of historical and cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
However, the rich tourism resources have not brought much
wealth to Tianshui, whose poor transport facilities are deemed as
a major barrier to the tourism boom in the city.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that only about 800,000 visitors tour the city
each year, and an overwhelming majority of them come from
neighboring provinces.
</P>
<P>
The local government has come to realize the importance of good
transportation, and lots of effort has been put into improving the
city's infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
According to Sun, a high-quality road connecting the city with
the northwest transportation hub, Xi'an, will soon to be finished
and a large airport is scheduled to be completed in four years.
</P>
<P>
The city will also build a highway exclusively for tourists,
which will link downtown Tianshui with the Maijishan Grottos, a
major tourism resort with equal fame as the renowned Dunhuang
Grottos, Sun said.
</P>
<P>
"Once the problem of transportation is solved, we will
certainly witness the booming of Tianshui's tourism," Sun said
with confidence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Grottoes to Apply for World Heritage List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANSHUI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Maiji Mountain Grottoes, known
as the "Oriental Sculpture Museum", in Tianshui, west China's
Gansu Province, will apply to the United Nations' Educational
Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) for the World
Heritage List.
</P>
<P>
With more than 1,600 years of history, the grottoes contain
over 7,000 pieces of clay sculpture, which are of high artistic
and academic value, said Hu Chengzu, head of the Maiji Grottoes
Art Institute.
</P>
<P>
He said relevant government departments are now involved in
preparing apply to both the world natural and cultural heritage
lists.
</P>
<P>
The grottoes were built on cliffs, 80 meters above the ground,
in 402 A.D. and have been improved over a dozen dynasties
including Northern Wei (386-534), Western Wei (535-556), Northern
Zhou (557-581), Sui (581-618), Tang (618-907), the period of Five
Dynasties (907-960), Song (960-1279), Yuan (1271-1368), Ming (1368-
-1644) and Qing (1644--1911), and have created a history of China'
s sculpture art.
</P>
<P>
Located beside the Tianshui, a major city in east Gansu, the
grottoes, along with Mogao Grottoes in the province's Dunhuang
area, Yungang Grottoes in Shanxi Province, and Longmen Grottoes in
Henan province, are the four most famous grottoes in China.
</P>
<P>
In addition to clay sculptures, there are a total of 1,300
square meters of frescos and more than 2,000 pieces of pottery,
bronzeware, ironware, jade articles, ancient books, documents,
paintings, calligraphy and other cultural relics in the 194
grottoes.
</P>
<P>
"It is really a miracle that all those clay sculptures and
other relics are preserved so well after more than 1,600 years,"
said Hu, adding that the grottoes remain the biggest grottoes in
the world which have such a large number of clay sculptures.
</P>
<P>
The Tianshui municipal government has already issued a long-
term program to protect the relics in the grottoes and has begun
to collect data on the geography, water, temperature and moisture
in the environment surrounding Maiji Mountain.
</P>
<P>
The local government will also clear the illegal construction
around the grottoes and organize farmers to return land for
farming to forestry to meet the standards of the world heritage
application. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reformist Writer Arrested in Tehran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Ahmad Zeid-Abadi, a writer working
with the Tehran-based daily Hamshahri (Citizen), was detained
Monday morning under an order issued by the press court.
</P>
<P>
Zeid-Abadi, who also worked with other periodicals, was taken
away by a group of more than 10 people who claimed they were acting
on behalf of the court dealing with offences committed by
government employees, the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
Zeid-Abadi's wife Mahdiyeh Mohammadi told reporters that the
group searched their house thoroughly and took away some of the
writings and documents belonging to her husband.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a judge of the Tehran press court confirmed the
detention of Zeid-Abadi, saying he was arrested because he had
defied an earlier call to report to the court.
</P>
<P>
Hamshahri, run by the Tehran municipality, is one of the few
pro-reform papers left since the conservative judiciary launched a
massive crackdown on reformist press in April.
</P>
<P>
So far some 21 papers and journals, most of them pro-reform
ones, have been closed down by the judiciary on the so-called
charges of defamation and violating Islamic values.
</P>
<P>
The judiciary has also ordered the arrest of a number of other
reformist journalists on similar charges. Zeid-Abadi was only the
latest case.
</P>
<P>
The press law, which was amended by the previous conservative-
dominated Majlis (parliament), has served as a powerful tool for
the judiciary to crack down on pro-reform papers and journalists.
</P>
<P>
Reformists, who won an overwhelming victory in February's
parliamentary election, pledged to overturn the restrictive clauses
in the press law in open sessions of the new Majlis, which started
work on May 27.
</P>
<P>
But on Sunday, reformers opened their session in disappointment
because Majlis Speaker Mehdi Karrubi announced a scheduled debate
on rewriting the press law had been withdrawn from the Majlis
agenda.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made on an order from supreme leader Ayatollah
Ali Khamenei, who had reportedly written a letter to the Majlis,
saying that rewriting the press law in such a juncture is against
the interests of the state and the system.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that the supreme leader, who is believed
to stand by the conservatives, made a direct intervention on Majlis
affairs. Khamenei's intervention was clearly a severe setback for
reformers, more than two months after they started work in the
Majlis.
</P>
<P>
Karrubi's announcement on Sunday sparked a brawl among
parliament members, some even engaged in physical scuffling on the
Majlis floor. It was the first such event since the new Majlis
started work, but obviously it was not the last.
</P>
<P>
With the precedent of Khamenei's direct intervention, it will be
very difficult for the new Majlis to carry out its work, which, as
reformers pledged in election campaigns, will focus on pushing
forward President Mohammad Khatami's reform programs.
</P>
<P>
President Khatami has announced his decision to seek re-election
in next year's presidential election. In such a situation, the
factional struggle in Iran will certainly accelerate in the coming
months.
</P>
<P>
According to an IRNA report, some 50 conservative figures
gathered in front of the Majlis building here Sunday evening to
protest the brawl by some parliament members over Khamenei's order
to cancel the debate on the press law.
</P>
<P>
The protesters slammed the performance of the Ministry of
Culture and Islamic Guidance for its encouragement of press
freedom.
</P>
<P>
A cleric addressing the protesters also blasted certain bills
currently being reviewed by the reformist Majlis, terming some of
the Majlis members as agents of foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The protest was clearly pre-organized by the conservative
establishment, as an IRNA correspondent covering the news of the
protest was detained for one hour by two armed officers and thus
was not able to thoroughly report the event, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
