<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Anti-Money Laundering Law to Be Effective in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A new law aimed at fighting money
laundering is expected to take effect from mid-September in
Thailand, an official report said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The law, designed to deter illegal activities, was originally
supposed to take effect in last August, but was postponed because
of technicalities and fears of possible loopholes, according to
the report, which was released by Thai government.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, it said, banks must report deposits exceeding
two million baht ( 50,000 U.S. dollars ), as well as the source of
the funds, to the Anti-Money Laundering Office (AMLO).
</P>
<P>
However, some banks said they won't be ready by mid-September
because providing depositor information to AMLO is laborious,
taking time and increasing operating costs.
</P>
<P>
AMLO Secretary-General Vasana Puemlarp recently opposed the
banks' move to delay the implementation of the law, arguing that
they had been notified long before the effective date.
</P>
<P>
The law was drafted in line with the United Nations'
conventions against illicit drug trades to prevent criminals from
using their illegally-acquired wealth to influence politics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Countries Asked to Cooperate in Fire-Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Monday called upon
Asian countries to adopt a systematic trans-boundary cooperation
in fire-fighting.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Housing and Local Government Minister Ong Ka Ting
made the call when opening the 21st International Fire Chiefs'
Association of Asia (IFCAA) general conference here.
</P>
<P>
Such cooperation was reflected in the successful collaboration
between Malaysia and Indonesia in dousing widespread forest fires
in Kalimantan and Sumatra which caused the haze in the region in
1997, Ong Ka Ting said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian-Indonesian fire-fighters were able to contain the
forest fire within 16 days, he said, adding "This is a showcase to
prove that systematic cooperation across countries and borders can
overcome adverse situations caused by fire disasters."
</P>
<P>
The two-day IFCAA conference, themed "Fire Safety and Disaster
Management -- A Borderless Approach", are believed to act as a
catalyst to form better systematic trans-boundary cooperation
among its 18 members in fire-fighting, and to promote research,
expertise exchange and sharing contemporary developments in safety
and disaster management.
</P>
<P>
The association is rotating its biennial general conference
among its members to promote cooperation and the exchange of
knowledge in fire-fighting.
</P>
<P>
At the conference here, 14 papers were tabled by speakers from
Australia; China's Taipei; Hong Kong, China; Japan; the
Netherlands; Malaysia; Singapore; United Kingdom and United States.
</P>
<P>
And in conjunction with the conference, the Malaysian Fire
Protection Association (MFPA) is holding an exhibition of the
latest fire safety products from 40 companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
