<HEADLINE> Three Injured in Indonesia's Oil Refinery's Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- An oil refinery in Indonesia's
South Kalimantan province was reportedly caught fire on Monday
morning, injuring three workers, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The fire triggered panic that the country may face oil shortage,
said the report Monday.
</P>
<P>
It said that the oil refinery belonging to the state-owned oil
and gas company PT Pertamina in Balikpapan, South Kalimantan
province, caught fire and exploded on Monday morning at about 06:
45 a.m. (local time).
</P>
<P>
Three people, all Pertamina workers, were reportedly injured
due to the explosion which was described as a powerful bomb blast.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Mines and Energy Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono suggested
sabotage and terror action in the incident which coincided with
the opening of the Assembly's annual session.
</P>
<P>
"There is an indication of sabotage. But such a thing is not
confirmed yet," Yudhoyono told reporters in the sideline of the
Assembly's session.
</P>
<P>
He said that he has asked the police as well as the Indonesian
Military (TNI) to launch an investigation into the explosion, "
including to safeguard another important public facilities," he
said.
</P>
<P>
But, an interim report issued by the local police said that the
police found no evidences on the possible terror action or
sabotage in the incident, saying "it is purely an accident."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a Spokesman of the local authority W.W.F. Welan was
quoted as saying that the explosion will reduce the country's oil
production about 20,000 barrels per day. "It means that Balikpapan
may face premium shortage," Welan said, adding that the refinery
has now returned to a normal condition as soon as the firemen were
able to overcome the fire.
</P>
<P>
Earlier the total production of the refinery reached 265,000
barrels of oil per day.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the country was forced to import premium from
neighboring countries in its bid to meet the premium need in the
country. The country faced premium shortage last month due to the
damage of oil refinery in Balongan, West Java province.
</P>
<P>
The accident has triggered panic and aroused speculations that
such a thing was part of the effort from political opponents of
incumbent President to unseat him ahead the annual session of the
Assembly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
