<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Close Slightly Higher on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Share prices closed slightly
higher on Singapore Stock Market Monday but the market remained
fragile because of lack of fresh leads.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) gained 6.59 points to
close at 2,059.32 points in quiet trading.
</P>
<P>
The total volume was 316.16 million shares valued at 478.29
million Singapore dollars (about 277.22 million U.S. dollars).
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by 217 to 90 with 254
counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
SMRT, the government-linked company which runs Singapore's
subway system, was the most active stock as it registered a
turnover of 31.06 million units. MediaRing was the second largest
parcel on a volume of 14.08 million shares. PNE Ind was the next
with 13.89 million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
DBS led gainers of the day climbing by 50 cents to close at 21.
30 Singapore dollars. ICB went up 32 cents to finish at 3.62
Singapore dollars. SPH and SPH 100 edged up 30 cents to end at 27.
80 and 27.90 Singapore dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
OCBC topped the losers list as it gave up 70 cents to close at
12.10 Singapore dollars. Chartered and Venture shed 20 cents to
finish at 11.70 and 19.70 Singapore dollars respectively. F&AMP;N and
NatElec retreated 15 cents to end at 6.65 and 5.20 Singapore
dollars separately.
</P>
<P>
Dealers noted that there was a falling-off between open and
close in the movement of share prices Monday.
</P>
<P>
They also noted that the newly-listed SMRT hit a new high of 72
cents on fund buying before closing at 71.5 cents which
represented a 17 percent rise since its initial public offer price
of 61 cents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
