<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Probe Officials Supporting MILF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada ordered Monday government agencies to investigate
intelligence reports that several officials have been supporting
the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) in its fight against the
government.
</P>
<P>
The president issued the order to the Armed Forces of the
Philippines and the Philippine National Police during the cabinet
meeting at the Palace, the first since he arrived from an official
visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
"These people should be arrested and charged, if there is proof
of their involvement with the MILF. I don't care whether they are
senators, congressmen or any high official," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said he has yet to see the names in the list of alleged
MILF supporters, but pointed out that at least 50 names are listed
in the intelligence report.
</P>
<P>
He said government officials and employees were allegedly
providing
financial and other material support to the MILF to sustain its
war against the government, even after the fall of its camps.
</P>
<P>
During the cabinet meeting, Armed Forces chief of staff Angelo
Reyes admitted that among the "power factors" that have sustained
MILF's operations are the support of "a network of extremist
leaning politicians."
</P>
<P>
The network, according to Reyes, also includes "key government
officials, government contractors and professionals," although he
did not give details.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado, on his part, said initial
information reaching his office indicates that only officials in
the local level are involved with the MILF.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is the country's largest rebel group which has been
fighting for an independent Muslim state in Mindanao for more than
two decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
