<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Though Shas spiritual leader Rabbi Ovadia Yosef made a point
of calling the Holocaust martyrs "saints" in a sermon given Sunday
evening, the furor over his comments on the subject Saturday night
looked unlikely to abate.
</P>
<P>
In the earlier weekend sermon, Yosef had said the Jews who died
in the Holocaust were resurrected sinners being punished for crimes
committed in past lives.
</P>
<P>
He also denounced Prime Minister Ehud Barak as "senseless",
saying he is "running amok" in pursuit of peace with the Arabs, and
in doing so had "placed snakes in our midst. What kind of peace can
you make with a snake?" He further referred to the Palestinians
as "evil-doers."
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- No violence is expected between the Palestinians and Israel
in the foreseeable future, according to an updated Israel Defense
Forces Military Intelligence (MI) appraisal presented to the
General Staff last week.
</P>
<P>
The report says Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat is giving
absolute priority to bringing talks with Israel to a successful
conclusion. He is also inclining toward postponing the declaration
of an independent Palestinian state from the originally planned
September 13 to November 15 (the date on which the Palestinians
proclaimed their independence in 1988), or perhaps even to Fatah
Day on January 1.
</P>
<P>
MI disputes the assessments of senior officers in Central
Command that suggest the Palestinians want to achieve "independence
through confrontation" and will therefore initiate another round of
violence before the question of a permanent settlement with Israel
is resolved.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- The Chief Rabbinate Council will consider a proposal by
Rabbi, She'ar-Yishuv Hacohen, the Chief Rabbi of Haifa, on Monday
to establish a synagogue on the Temple Mount, a holy site which
Israel and the Palestinians had sovereignty disputes.
</P>
<P>
The discussion had drawn a warning from the Mufti of Jerusalem,
Ekrima Sa'id Sabri, who said Sunday that "if the Al-Aqsa Mosque (on
the Temple Mount) is harmed, not only the Muslims here but the
Muslims all over the world will not sit idly by."
</P>
<P>
Israel's two chief rabbis, Yisrael Meir Lau and Eliahu Bakshi-
Doron, are both against reversing the halakhic (Jewish Religious
Law's) stricture against Jews entering the Temple Mount compound
for reasons related to ritual uncleanness.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who has been in charge of no less
than 11 ministries over the last month, began divvying up the goods
Sunday, appointing caretaker ministers for four portfolios.
</P>
<P>
At Sunday's cabinet meeting, Barak made the following
appointments to portfolios that have been vacant since Shas, the
National Religious Party, and Yisrael Ba'aliya quit the government
last month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Barak is sending two ministers, Public Security
Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami and Transport and Tourism Minister Amnon
Lipkin-Shahak, on an overseas mission to explain the Israeli
positions put forward at Camp David. 
</P>
</TEXT>
