<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rebound Sharply in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rebounded sharply in
Tokyo Monday on bargain-hunting, with the benchmark Nikkei index
recovering to the 16,000 level for the first time in three trading
days.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange surged 335.35 points, or 2.14
percent, from last Friday's close to end at 16,002.71, after
losing some 540 points during the previous two trading days.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, gained 25.98 points, or 1.79 percent, to 1,
476.86.
</P>
<P>
Trading remained inactive throughout the day amid the summer
holiday season, with turnover on the major section falling to 442.
26 million shares from last Friday's 603.25 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Collapsed department store operator Sogo was the day's volume
leader.
</P>
<P>
High-priced information technology issues drew active buying
following last Friday's rise on Wall Street, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Brokerages also gained on reports that Japan's Big Three
brokerages have agreed to set up an online bond market for
institutional investors by spring next year.
</P>
<P>
The rubber sector was the only loser in the exchange's 33
business sectors.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers overwhelmed
losers 894 to 343, with 161 issues closing unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
