<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Says 160 Chechen Rebels Killed at Weekend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Russian military said Monday
that its artillery and air force killed about 160 rebels in the
republic of Chechnya during the air strikes and shelling last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
The federal forces pounded rebel concentrations in the forests
near Chechnya's capital of Grozny, the second biggest city of
Gudermes, Nozhai-Yurt and Urus-Martan districts, killing more than
160 rebel fighters and mercenaries and wounding scores of others,
the Interfax news agency quoted the press center of the Russian
Combined troops in the North Caucasus as saying.
</P>
<P>
The rebels' loss was especially severe in the forest north of
Gudermes, where Russian units found dozens of bodies of the
militants after federal air raids, according to the press center.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, who had infiltrated neighboring Ingushetia and
fired at several Russian helicopters Sunday, were killed in a
motor car while trying to escape. Under the rebels' fire, one of
the federal helicopters was forced to make an emergency landing
near a village in the Ingush republic's territory close to the
Chechen-Ingush border, with one of the 16 paratroopers on board
seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
On the whole, the rebels' threat to stage a large-scale
offensive on August 6, the so-called Ichkeria (rebels' Chechen
republic) Independence Day, did not materialize thanks to
preventive steps taken by the federal authorities, the press
center said.
</P>
<P>
There were no hit-and-run attacks or land mine explosions
reported in Grozny. Two rebels were fatally wounded there and
eight people were detained Sunday on suspicion of being members of
separatist bands.
</P>
<P>
An influential Chechen rebel field commander, former chief of
the Ichkeria security service Ibragim Khultygov surrendered to
federal units at the weekend, according to the press center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
