<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Turkish newspapers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet:
</P>
<P>
-- Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said on Sunday the
international community has begun to perceive the fact that "the
Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus (TRNC) is a separate and
independent state."
</P>
<P>
Ecevit made the remarks as the U.N.-brokered third round of
proximity talks on Cyprus ended on Friday in Geneva without any
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Rauf Denktash, leader of the self-acclaimed TRNC only recognized
by Turkey, said on Saturday in Istanbul that they did their best to
reach an agreement based on two independent states in Cyprus during
the talks, but Greek Cypriots showed no flexibility.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus was divided in 1974 when Turkey sent its troops to the
north following a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The fourth round of talks will start in New York on September
12.
</P>
<P>
Hurriyet:
</P>
<P>
-- Turkish State Minister Suayip Usenmez said on Sunday Turkey
will be dependent on other countries for oil, which has strategical
importance, adding production and search activities within the oil-
resource-poor country will stop as "these actions are not
economical."
</P>
<P>
Yenibinyil:
</P>
<P>
-- Turkish Tourism Minister Erkan Mumcu said on Sunday Turkey is
living in a "magnificent tourism season," adding the country hosted
1.5 million tourists in July.
</P>
<P>
He said the figure shows that Turkey will exceed the target of
10 million tourists for the whole year, predicting there is no
reason why the number cannot reach 12 million by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Daily News:
</P>
<P>
-- Turkish Forestry Ministry officials Sunday warned people
living in forest-intensive western and southern provinces, such as
Adana, Antalya, Balikesir, Izmir, Mersin, Mugla and Kahramanmaras,
against possible forest fires that might break out in these areas.
</P>
<P>
The ministry asked people not to light a fire in forests or
throw away burning cigarette buds, urging local authorities to
check the electricity transmitting cables passing from these areas.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, a total of 20,080 hectares of forest land were
burnt in Turkey by 153 fire spots, compared with last year's 1,496
hectares by 395 fire spots in the same period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
