<HEADLINE> Three Wounded by Israeli Fire at Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli soldiers on Sunday wounded
a 13-year-old boy who was hurling rocks at an observation post
beside the Fatima gate in the village of Kfar Kila and two
journalists nearby, An Nahar newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The two journalists, one from AFP and the other for Radio
Canada, were injured in abdomen and shoulder respectively while
Israeli soldiers fired back at the rock attackers. The wounded were
taken to hospital in Nabatieh.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Army said the teenager was wounded by a rock, not a
bullet during disturbances at the gate where Lebanese citizens
threw rocks, metal bars and bottles at Israeli soldiers and farmers
working on the far side of the border fence.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers fired warning shots into the air twice and then, when
they shot at the ground, a rock that was struck splintered and hit
the boy, the army said.
</P>
<P>
But a doctor at Nabatieh hospital said the boy was injured by a
bullet that ricocheted off the ground and into his foot.
</P>
<P>
Several Lebanese and Palestinian refugees have been wounded at
Fatima Gate since Israel's withdrawal from south Lebanon on May 24.
</P>
<P>
Israeli authority has warned its soldiers will be permitted to
fire back if rocks are thrown from the other side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
