<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Economy Recovers, President Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Abdurrahman
Wahid said here Monday that the country's economic situation is
now better than before, saying that the economy has now moved
away from the crisis circle.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before the annual session of the People's Consultative
Assembly to deliver a working report for his nine months in office,
Wahid said that the government has also made achievements over the
past nine months.
</P>
<P>
"The recovery programs having been implemented, our economy has
now moved away from the crisis circle, although it is still in the
early stage and is not strong enough yet," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The achievements made in the last nine months, although
objectively speaking many, are still meagre compared to the
expectations of the government itself as well also the assignment
it has to shoulder pursuant to the message of the Board Guidelines
of State Policy (GBHN), namely to meet the expectations of the
people at large," Wahid said.
</P>
<P>
In this occasion, Wahid also revealed the government policy in
the future to boost the ongoing economic recovery program.
</P>
<P>
"In the future, sustainable and just economic recovery will be
underpinned by four pillars of program, namely : the maintenance
of the macroeconomic stability, the strengthening of economic
institutions, the improvement of structural policies, and the
protection and the empowerment of those who have been left behind,
who don't have ability and who are poor," Wahid stressed.
</P>
<P>
He also said that in a bid to maintain a conducive
macroeconomic stability the government will continue its national
economic recovery efforts by inviting foreign investors to
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The president said the economic relations with other countries
should be directed towards utilizing all the potentials of these
countries which have financial capacity, managerial expertise,
technology and necessary networks.
</P>
<P>
Wahid added that in the area of monetary, the government will
continue to adopt a monetary policy in line with the economic
target and needs which have been fixed, citing that the government
will also honor the independence of Bank Indonesia, the country's
central bank, in determining monetary policies.
</P>
<P>
"In the context of maintaining macrostability, the government
will continue to cooperate constructively with the Bank Indonesia
to strengthen our economic fundamentals so that these will be
realistically reflected in the exchange rate of rupiah," Wahid
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
