<HEADLINE> U.S. Marines Join Battle Against Wildfires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 6 (Xinhua) -- As wildfires raged Sunday
across almost 750,000 acres in the western United States, more
troops moved into the state of Idaho to bolster firefighting
efforts.
</P>
<P>
"The Marines have landed!" said fire information officer Renee
Snyder, referring to 500 Marines from Camp Pendleton, California.
</P>
<P>
Troops were sent to Idaho's Salmon-Challis National Forest,
about 200 kilometers northeast of Boise, to help build a fire line
around the blaze, which was sparked by lightning on July 10.
</P>
<P>
Some 130 kilometers to the east, 500 Army soldiers from Fort
Hood, Texas, worked on mop-up duty at the Burgdorf Junction fire
in the Payette National Forest, where more than 22,000 acres have
burned. Another contingent from the same camp is scheduled to
arrive soon.
</P>
<P>
In Idaho, even as word came that beleaguered crews would get
reinforcements from Canadian firefighters and more U.S. Army
troops, Gov. Dirk Kempthorne said it could be autumn before some
of the blazes in his state are controlled.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of blazes have made Montana a leading hot spot on the
West's fire map. Sixteen large fires in the state have burned
about 140,000 acres so far.
</P>
<P>
"The Northern Rockies area is the hottest place in the country
at the moment, and it's mostly Montana," said Lynn Pisano-Pedigo,
spokeswoman at the National Interagency Fire Center in Boise.
</P>
<P>
In California, eight new fires had scorched more than 88,450
acres by Saturday. The largest blaze -- 72,730 acres in the
Sequoia National Forest about 250 kilometers north of Los Angeles -
- was 80 percent contained, according to fire information officer
Gil Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
The estimated size of the area on fire in the West has jumped
by more than 200,000 acres since Saturday, according to new data
from airborne infrared cameras, the National Interagency Fire
Center said.
</P>
<P>
The center now counts 64 large wildfires covering 941,771 acres
up from 62 fires on 739,800 acres Saturday night in Arizona,
California, Colorado, Idaho, Montana, Nevada, New Mexico, Oregon,
Utah, Washington, and Wyoming,
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton is expected to tour Idaho's fire areas
Tuesday and speak with some of the more than 1,500 military troops
who have been sent in to help exhausted civilian fire crews, the
White House announced Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Officials said about 20,000 firefighters have been struggling
to contain the fires, which so far this year have burned 3.9
million acres in 63,242 blazes, nearly twice as big an area as
normal.
</P>
<P>
Forecasts on Sunday offered little hope of relief from the hot,
dry weather that has helped create what officials have called the
worst fire season in the West in 50 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
