<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daily Air Quality Report for 42 Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Two Chinese cities, namely
Taiyuan and Xi'an, reported slight air pollution today.
</P>
<P>
According to a daily air quality report issued by the China
Environmental Monitoring Center, level two or fairly good air
quality was recorded in the following 28 cities: Beijing, Tianjin,
Shijiazhuang, Hohhot, Shenyang, Changchun, Harbin, Nanjing,
Hangzhou, Wenzhou, Hefei, Fuzhou, Nanchang, Jinan, Yantai,
Zhengzhou, Wuhan, Changsha, Guangzhou, Zhanjiang, Chongqing,
Chengdu, Guiyang, Kunming, Lhasa, Lanzhou, Xining and Urumqi.
</P>
<P>
Particulates less than 10 microns in size were the major
pollutants in most of the cities, except Chongqing, Guiyang and
Kunming, where sulfur dioxide was the major air pollutant.
</P>
<P>
Twelve cities -- Dalian, Shanghai, Suzhou, Nantong, Xiamen,
Qingdao, Shenzhen, Zhuhai, Shantou, Nanning, Haikou, Yinchuan --
reported excellent air.
</P>
<P>
The center classifies air quality in China's urban areas into
five levels: level one or excellent (pollution readings: not
exceeding 50), level two or fairly good (pollution readings: 51 to
100), level three or slightly polluted (pollution readings: 101-
200), level four or poor (pollution readings: 201-300), and level
five or hazardous (pollution readings: over 301).
</P>
<P>
The 42 cities monitored by the center include the four
municipalities of Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Chongqing,
provincial capitals and major cities in the economically developed
coastal areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wahid: Conflicts, Power Struggle Threaten Indonesia's Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 7 (Xinhua) - Indonesian President Abdurrahman
Wahid said here Monday that mounting conflicts and power struggle
among elite politicians and forces in Indonesia is really
threatening the existence of the unitary state and national
integrity.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the annual session of the country's highest law-
making body of the Peoples Consultative Assembly (MPR), the
president said that the government faces difficulties due to a
wide spread communal conflict.
</P>
<P>
"The political atmosphere, we feel, is flowing and affecting
the intensity of controversy and physical conflicts among certain
parts of our society," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the area of security and politics, Wahid said, his
government inherited a situation that is laden with conflict of
interest, followed everywhere by various law violations.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that, "even though the government that was formed
from the result of the 1999 general elections already possessed
legitimization and reflects the will and desire of the people, its
existence cannot automatically cool down the atmosphere of
conflict, which deeply rooted in politics, economy and society."
</P>
<P>
The annual session of the assembly was opened by its Speaker
Amien Rais on Monday morning and is expected to be closed on
August 18.
</P>
<P>
All factions in the Assembly will express their respective
opinions, questions and criticism of the President's speech until
August 9.
</P>
<P>
But there is no sign, so far, that the president will be
impeached due to his alleged failure in dealing with the huge
complex problems which have been deteriorating economic and
political situation in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
