<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Ruling Party Lawmaker Crosses Over to Main Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's member of Parliament
Dixon Perera of the ruling People's Alliance (PA) on Monday
crossed over to the main opposition United National Party (UNP) at
the beginning of the parliamentary debate on the government's
contentious new draft constitution.
</P>
<P>
Perera is the PA member of Parliament for the district of
Colombo. His crossover is viewed as a major blow to the government
who is trying to muster a two-thirds majority or 150 votes to push
through the draft in the 225-seat parliament.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said the government is short of 25 votes due to
the crossover of Perera and the noncooperation of the UNP and some
Tamil parties.
</P>
<P>
The Leader of the Sri Lanka Muslim Congress M. Ashraff opened
the debate in the parliament Monday morning on the new
constitution which aims at politically resolving the 17-year civil
war between majority Sinhalese dominated government troops and
Tamil Tiger rebels who demand a separate state in Sri Lanka's
north and east. The debate was covered live on the national
television.
</P>
<P>
The UNP leader Ranil Wickremesinghe is scheduled to make a
statement to the parliament on Monday and then the party would
stage a walk out. The three-day debate began amidst growing
opposition to the reforms.
</P>
<P>
The UNP had a meeting last night where all their members of
parliament agreed to support the party line.
</P>
<P>
However two UNP members of Parliament who are accused of
crossing over to the government side on Monday had not presented
themselves at the meeting. They are Mervyn de Silva, member of
Parliament from the south of Sri Lanka, and Sarath Kongahage from
the central hills of the country.
</P>
<P>
The PA government of President Kumaratunga has been lobbying
heavily to woo the UNP members of Parliament. It was confirmed by
Minister of Environment Mahinda Wijesekara in a speech made over
the national television. He said, "We have the right to speak to
the opposition members to get their support." 
</P>
</TEXT>
