<HEADLINE> Thailand Moves to Crack Down Jewel Scams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Thai tourist police are working
with the Tourism Authority of Thailand and other agencies
concerned to curb the long-standing problem of jewelry scams, the
Bangkok Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Unscrupulous jewelry companies, tuk tuk drivers, illegal tour
guides, commercial bank staff and tour operators are all involved
in duping foreign tourists into buying high-priced cheap jewelry,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The authorities are working with the Thai Gem and Jewelry
Traders Association to establish common standards and a
recognizable logo that visitors can use to identify reputable
stores, Chanaphat Choeisombat, superintendent of the tourist
police, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said brochures advising foreign visitors to be aware of
being cheated will be distributed on flights coming into Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Tourist police have been instructed to patrol popular areas and
keep a close watch on tuk tuk drivers and illegal tour guides who
approach foreign tourists.
</P>
<P>
The commerce ministry is also helping with the investigation,
and the revenue department of the finance ministry has been asked
to inspect tax payments of shops suspected of being involved in
scams, and tour companies are being warned they could face
deregistration.
</P>
<P>
About 477 tourists, mostly Westerners and Japanese, complained
of being defrauded by gem dealers last year. About 120 tourists
have filed complaints so far this year.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 people were arrested in relation to running gem scams
each month and were charged with causing a nuisance to others and
fined a maximum of 1,000 baht, Chanaphat said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
