<HEADLINE> Philippines Plans to Borrow 4.43 Bln Dollars Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
proposing to raise some 177.3 billion pesos (4.43 billion U.S.
dollars) in foreign and local borrowings next year to finance the
expected budget deficit of 85 billion pesos (2.13 billion dollars)
for the year 2001,a local newspaper said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Daily Inquirer quoted data from Department of Budget and
Management as saying that the total borrowings would also be used
to settle maturing obligations of 81.6 billion pesos (2.04 billion
dollars) and bring down the Treasury balance by 6 billion pesos (
150 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
"This borrowing level is 59.8 billion pesos (1.5 billion
dollars)lower than the 237.1-billion-peso (5.9 billion dollars)
borrowing level for 2000, significant inasmuch as the budget
deficit for 2001 is higher than the 62.5-billion-peso (1.56
billion dollars) programmed deficit for this year," said the paper.
</P>
<P>
Of the proposed 177.3-billion-peso borrowings, the government
plans to borrow 112.3 billion pesos (2.8 billion dollars) from
domestic market, while 65 billion pesos (1.6 billion dollars) will
come from abroad, the paper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
