<HEADLINE> World Congress on Forestry Research Opens in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The 21st International Union
of Forestry Research Organizations (IUFRO) World Congress opened
here Monday to address issues of future developments of forest
research in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The six-day congress, themed "Forests and Society: The Role of
Research," will focus on subjects such as sustainable forest
management, forests and society needs, environment change and
forests, economic and social aspects of forestry in developing
countries, and management of forestry research.
</P>
<P>
Some 2500 participants from 91 countries and regions are
attending the congress, the first being held in a developing
country since IUFRO was established in 1892 to promote
international cooperation in forestry research and related
sciences.
</P>
<P>
At the official opening of the congress, Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad urged the developed countries to
reaffirm and put into action their commitments to provide concrete
financial assistance and technologies to developing countries to
achieve sustainable management of their forests.
</P>
<P>
"If the world is to achieve sustainable forest management, the
transfer of technology from the North to the South on preferential
terms as agreed to in Rio must be forthcoming," Mahathir said in
his keynote address delivered by Primary Industries Minister Lim
Keng Yaik.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir believed IUFRO can play an important role to
facilitate this transfer of technology, hoping this congress will
help develop more concrete networks which will serve as effective
conduits for North-South transfer of technology.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need for a legally-binding instrument for
addressing a whole range of issues on forestry and timber in a
holistic, integrated and comprehensive manner to facilitate the
achievement of sustainable forest management. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
