<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Imposes Restrictions on Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
imposed restrictions on foreign investment in several sectors, the
Jakarta Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
In addition to radio, television broadcasting, print,
information and multimedia services, the new investment regulation
also prohibits foreign investment in logging activities in natural
forests, public transportation (taxi and bus services), inter-
island shipping services, except large-scale retail services such
as supermarket, department stores and large-scale wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
Exhibition and convention activities, quality certification
services, warehousing outside of sea ports and ship maintenance
services are also exempt from the ban.
</P>
<P>
According to the new investment regulation, dated July 20 and
effective immediately, foreign investors are also prohibited from
investing in sectors like movie production activities such as
production, technical filming services, exportation and
importation of movies, movie distribution and movie screening;
radio and television broadcasting, including pay and cable
television services; information and multimedia services; and
printed mass media.
</P>
<P>
The new investment regulation allows foreign investors to enter
some restricted business sectors but with limitations, such as a
requirement to establish a joint venture with local partners.
</P>
<P>
The business sectors in which foreign investors are allowed to
enter but only through a joint venture with local partners, in
which they can own up to 95 percent of a company, are port
construction and management; power generation, transmission and
distribution; ocean freight services; processing and distribution
of drinking water for the public; public train services; atomic
power generation; and hospital-related services, including
hospital management, medical checkups; laboratory management,
health insurance; medical equipment distribution; and health
services.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors are also allowed to set up business with
local partners in telecommunications and airline companies, but
can control only up to 49 percent of a company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tight Security Imposed Around Sri Lankan Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Security around the Sri Lankan
Parliament will be tightened between Monday and Friday when the
proposed new constitution and proposals for a new electoral system
will be debated, the official Daily News reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Inspector General of Police of Western Province (South)
Jayantha Wickremaratne was quoted as saying that intelligence
reports had been received that several organizations will attempt
to disrupt the peace during the proceedings of the parliament.
</P>
<P>
In addition to tight security, traffic in the parliament area
in eastern suburban Colombo will also be curtailed during the
proceedings and the public has been requested to use alternative
roads.
</P>
<P>
The government has decided to go ahead with the new legislation
despite mounting opposition from political parties, national
organizations and the powerful Buddhist clergy claiming that there
was inadequate public debate on the proposed new laws.
</P>
<P>
They have also expressed surprise at the government's haste to
rush through the legislation when the parliament will be dissolved
on August 24 and the next general elections must be held by early
November.
</P>
<P>
A two-thirds majority in the parliament is required for the
legislation to be passed and government is banking on a crossover
of at least 15 members of the main opposition United National
Party to obtain it.
</P>
<P>
The Buddhist clergy and other organizations have called on all
members of the parliament to oppose the legislation which they
describe as anti-national.
</P>
<P>
The government, however, sees the new legislation as a
political solution to the country's ethnic conflict, which has
seen a 17-year war during which more than 60,000 persons have been
killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
