<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Dubai Millennium" Retired After Severe Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Fate dealt Dubai's Godolphin
stable a cruel blow on Saturday, when the world's most famous
racing operation lost it's "dream" performer Dubai Millennium to a
freak accident on the Newmarket Gallops in England.
</P>
<P>
Dubai Millennium, as his owner-breeder General Mohammed bin
Rashid Al Maktoum, crown prince of Dubai and minister of Defence,
called "the best horse he has every seen," was discovered by his
trainer Saeed bin Suroor to have suffered a severe fracture of his
right hind leg shortly after working on the Limekilns.
</P>
<P>
A hastily arranged x-ray revealed that the "lateral condylar
fracture" was in fact career-ending injury and meant that the four-
year-old colt would never set foot on a race track again. He was
immediately retired to stud, according to local media on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We're devastated," Suroor told the United Arab Emirates media
from Newmarket, "it's the worst news we could have ever had. The
vet informed us that he will require surgery for this serious
injury which means that his career is over."
</P>
<P>
The news that sent shock waves through the racing industry came
only hours after General Mohammed had proposed a sensational 12
million U.S. dollars match race with French champion Montjeu, a
clash that would have fired the imagination of racegoers across
the globe.
</P>
<P>
Suroor was on hand to supervise Dubai Millennium's gallop under
regular work rider 'Tony', and said that the Dubai World Cup
winner had turned in a typically brilliant piece of work. "He
looked to be in his best shape," said Suroor. "He worked fantastic
and completely outran his lead horse Fly To The Stars.
</P>
<P>
"But as we were leading him to his stable I noticed a swelling
on his right hind leg. On closer examination I discovered it was
pretty serious and was immediately worried," said Suroor
describing the incident. "We quickly arranged for an x-ray, which
revealed that he needed a major operation and that there was no
way he would ever race again.
</P>
<P>
"We contacted General Mohammed instructed that he will be
retired to stud in Darley where he will stand as a stallion," he
added.
</P>
<P>
In an announcement on Godolphin's website, General Mohammed had
thrown down the gauntlet of a contest, which was scheduled just
eight days before, to Montjeu's owner Michael Tabor, inviting him
to race Montjeu against Dubai Millennium for a winner's purse of 6
million dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
