<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Cement Production Picks Up in 1999-2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's cement production picked
up in fiscal year 1999-2000, which ended in March, with 350,784
tons following a three consecutive years' fall in the output since
1995-96, according to the latest issue of the official Economic
Indicators available Monday.
</P>
<P>
The country's cement production fell from 523,611 tons in 1995-
96 to 501,989 tons in 1996-97, 483,442 tons in 1997-98 and then to
333,513 tons in 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
Because of the fall, the country spent in 1997-98 83.7 million
U.S. dollars importing cement.
</P>
<P>
The expenditure was then reduced to 65.5 million in 1998-99 and
42.1 million in 1999-2000, while endeavors for boosting cement
production were made in order to save the foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of the rising demand for cement in its
infrastructural construction such as roads, bridges and dams,
Myanmar is also making efforts to build more cement plants.
</P>
<P>
In last June, Myanmar signed an accord with a Chinese company
to build a 500-ton-daily-capacity cement plant in Kyaukse, central
Mandalay division of the country.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Myanmar is also trying to get a foreign
loan of 150 million dollars to build a 4,000-ton daily-capacity
large-scale cement plant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
