<HEADLINE> Bomber Still at Large, Says Indonesian Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian authorities are
working closely with U.S. investigators in a bid to track down
whoever planted a bomb that exploded outside the Philippine
ambassador's residence in Central Jakarta last week.
</P>
<P>
"We are coordinating with the U.S. to exchange all sorts of
information, ranging from the type of the bomb to the suspects,"
National Police chief General Rusdihardjo was quoted by Indonesian
Observer Monday as saying.
</P>
<P>
He hinted that the bomb may not have been from Indonesia and
there is a possibility that the bomb was made in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
"That's a possibility. We are still looking forward to
searching for the producer and the suspect," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rusdihardjo said police have accepted U.S. help in order to
close the case as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
"We are also working with the TNI (Indonesian Defense Forces),"
he added.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Philippines has offered to help
Indonesian investigators find the bombers.
</P>
<P>
The August 1 bombing killed two persons and injured 22,
including the Philippine ambassador. 
</P>
