<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Assembly Starts Annual Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The People's Consultative
Assembly (MPR), Indonesia's highest decision-making body, opened
its annual session here Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
The 12-day meeting will listen to President Abdurrahman Wahid's
working report on Monday noon. The presidential report will
reportedly focus on inter-religious tolerance, the supremacy of
the law and equality.
</P>
<P>
After hearing Wahid's working report, MPR factions will express
their respective opinions, questions or criticism of the president
's speech until August 9.
</P>
<P>
The president is scheduled to appear again at the MPR on
Wednesday evening to reply to the Assembly's factions.
</P>
<P>
Besides the president, all high government institutions,
including the National Audit Body, the Supreme Court and Supreme
Advisory Body, will also have to present their working report, but
in no case will there be a vote of acceptance or rejection.
</P>
<P>
The 700 MPR members will also discuss and decide on 20-odd
proposed amendments to the 1945 Constitution.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to make the meeting successful, about 66,300 security
personnel were deployed in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
Several mass public gatherings were held in Jakarta and other
cities in recent weeks, calling for an end to bloodshed across the
country.
</P>
<P>
Coordinating Minister for People's Welfare and Poverty
Eradication Basri Hasanuddin on Sunday also launched a peace
campaign here, calling on people of different faiths, races and
tribes to uphold love and affection.
</P>
<P>
Communal violence between Christians and Muslims has broken out
in several regions in Indonesia in the past months, including
Maluku, North Maluku, Central Sulawesi and Central Kalimantan
provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
