<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Sports Beat Esperance 2-1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Africa Sports, helped by
striker Fadel Keita who is the top goalscorer in this year's
African Champions League, defeated favorite Esperance 2-1 in
group one of the competition on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Keita, who scored five goals in four matches in the first two
knockout rounds, returned from a broken jaw to net twice in the
opening 15 minutes in Abidjan as the home side scored their first
points of the league phase of the Champions League.
</P>
<P>
The result restored the Ivorian club's chances in the
competition after they lost their opening group match to Mamelodi
Sundowns of South Africa a fortnight ago.
</P>
<P>
Esperance still leads the group on goal difference from Africa
Sports and Sundowns, whose game away at Sable de Batie of Cameroon
in Douala was postponed on Sunday because of heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
The big weekend winners were Ghana's Hearts of Oak, who scored
a 4-2 away win over Jeanne d'Arc of Senegal on Saturday to take
the lead in group two.
</P>
<P>
The four goals were the most scored by a visiting team since
the league format was introduced in 1997.
</P>
<P>
It was another player returning to action who stole the show,
18-year-old Ishmael Addo scoring twice for the Ghanaian side in
Dakar.
</P>
<P>
Addo, suspended for Hearts' last game in the Champions League,
scored twice in the second half to break a 1-1 deadlock at the
interval.
</P>
<P>
Hearts of Oak lead the group two standings with a full haul of
points from their opening two matches, followed by Al Ahli of
Egypt, who have three points from their 3-1 win over Lobi Stars in
Cairo on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
The next round of matches in the two groups are to be played
on August 19-20. The two group winners meet in the Champions
League, to be played over two legs, in December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
