<HEADLINE> Bubka Remains Optimistic about Olympic Chances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KIEV, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Sergei Bubka failed to clear his
opening height at the Ukrainian national championships Sunday but
he remained optimistic about his Olympic pole vault chances.
</P>
<P>
The six times world champion missed twice at 5.60 meters,
raised the bar to 5.72 for his third attempt but knocked it down
again.
</P>
<P>
Denis Yurchenko from Bubka's home town of Donetsk won the
competition with a personal best 5.72.
</P>
<P>
The 36-year-old Bubka, who has been battling a serious
Achilles tendon injury for several years, was not disappointed
with his performance.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not disappointed at all with my performance tonight," he
was quoted as saying. "The main thing for me was that I didn't
feel any pain in my leg, which I had just a month ago.
</P>
<P>
"I haven't jumped much this season and my timing is off,
therefore I intend to compete as often as possible until Sydney."
</P>
<P>
He is planning to compete every week this month, beginning in
Zurich on August 11th.
</P>
<P>
Bubka is expected to make his farewell appearance in the
Sydney Olympics next month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
