<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Deny Preparations for New Camp David Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Mahmoud Abbas, Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat's deputy, here Monday denied that there have
been preparations for a second Camp David summit to work out a
permanent peace deal between Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Abbas, also known as Abu Mazen, is secretary general of the
Executive Committee of Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO). He
was accompanying Arafat in a multi-national tour to rally support
for Palestinian positions.
</P>
<P>
He said before the departure of the Palestinian delegation that
any future summit should be well prepared. Arafat left here Monday
evening after concluding a one-day visit to the United Arab
Emirates.
</P>
<P>
Abbas praised the UAE's repeated call for an Arab summit, saying
Palestinians want the summit to be held on the issue of Jerusalem
so that all Arabs could take their share of responsibility on the
issue of Jerusalem, according to the official WAM news agency.
</P>
<P>
He said that Arafat had briefed Khalifa bin Zayed al Nahyan, Abu
Dhabi crown prince and deputy supreme commander of the armed
forces, on the outcome of the difficult days that the Palestinian
team had spent at the failed Camp David summit.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Arafat accused Israel of wanting "Tailor-made
peace." But he said another U.S.-sponsored summit would possibly be
held after August 14, whereas Israeli Prime Minister Barak declared
it is "too early to discuss new summit." 
</P>
</TEXT>
