<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Boosts Campaign Against Far-Right Extremism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The German government Monday
announced that it would launch a federal wide project as its
latest action against the swelling far-right racism.
</P>
<P>
In the initiative named "Show Face," leading roles in all
fields of German society will speak out in television, radio and
other media to encourage the public's rejection of racism,
government spokesman Uwe-Karsten Heye told a press conference in
Duesseldorf.
</P>
<P>
The project, due to begin in September, is an "all German
action," Heye stressed, adding that Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder
will set the campaign against far-right extremists a major task
after his summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder's wife Doris Schroeder-Koepf will work for the
initiative together with a dozen sports, film and television stars,
said Heye.
</P>
<P>
German Jewish leaders, also appearing at the press conference
broadcast by the Pheonix television, called the recent increase of
neo-Nazi violence "serious" and "intolerable."
</P>
<P>
"We cannot allow a handful of criminals to destroy what have
been built up in the past 55 years," said Paul Spiegel, chairman
of the Central Council of Jews in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Facing a series of far-right violence and indications that
German far-rightists are expanding their influence, politicians of
both the ruling Social Democratic Party (SPD) and its conservative
opposition Christian Democratic Union (CDU) Monday called on the
social courage to fight back.
</P>
<P>
Agela Merkel, chairwoman of the CDU, pledged more "
concentrated actions" in German youngsters against far-right
extremism, and said the government should totally prohibit neo-
Nazi demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
"There is too much looking-away, too much fear.... We should
show our social courage," she told the ZDF television.
</P>
<P>
German Interior Minister Otto Schily said last weekend he
planned to deploy the elite Federal Border Protection police
forces to help local authorities cope with the far-right crimes.
</P>
<P>
Wolfgang Clement, SPD premier of Germany's most populous North
Rhine-Westphalia state, Monday vowed to ban hard-core far-right
groups such as the National Democratic Party (NPD).
</P>
<P>
The NPD's flagrant propaganda for anti-Semitism violence has
aroused widespread outrage. A special parliamentary committee will
launch investigations into the party and in a poll most law-
enforcement agents agree to prohibit it.
</P>
<P>
The Bild newspaper reported Monday there were 760 cases of far-
right offenses against 838 people during the first half of this
year, growing monthly by about 10 percent. Thirty-one cases were
convicted, and 96.3 percent of the suspects were freed.
</P>
<P>
Another report in the Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung newspaper
said the far-right groups were using the Internet as their major
propaganda base.
</P>
<P>
An Internet domain name firm in Frankfurt said someone had
registered a web site named www.Heil-Hitler.de, offending the
ultimate taboo of post-war German society.
</P>
<P>
Just on Monday, two cases of crime suspected to be of neo-Nazi
background were reported. In Bavaria state, the police found a
bomb near a Jewish house and in Rhineland-Palatinate state, a
Jewish cemetery was found painted with Nazi swastikas.
</P>
<P>
In a poll released last weekend, some 89 percent of plain
Germans said the government was "incompetent" in fighting against
far-right extremism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Software Maker to Spin off Software Service Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CA founder Charles Wang, who remains as chairman while
relinquishing his CEO position to CA president Sanjay Kumar, told
a press conference that he will focus on new initiatives to "
unlock value for shareholders".
</P>
<P>
According to a company statement, the ASP company is formed to
serve customers selling Internet-based software services to
businesses.
</P>
<P>
ASP is a young industry with growth potential. The
International Data Corporation predicted a 90% annual growth, from
a very low revenue level in 1998 to 2 billion dollars by 2003.
</P>
<P>
Wang said CA intends to become an e-business related software
leader and will intensify efforts to roll out security,
application development and business intelligence products, its
fastest-growing lines.
</P>
<P>
CA, founded in 1076, employs 20,000 people. It delivers end-to-
end infrastructure to enable e-business through technology,
service and education. Its sales revenue exceeded 6 billion
dollars in the fiscal year ending March 31, 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
