<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 21st Century To Be L. American Century: Mexican President-Elect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Mexican President-elect Vicente
Fox has said the 21st century will be a Latin American century,
and proposed to strengthen the Organization of American States (
OAS) and the Inter-American Development Bank (IDB).
</P>
<P>
"In general we Latin Americans did not do too fine in the 20th
century," said Fox, referring to the continuos economic crisis in
the region, during an interview released Monday by the Venezuelan
newspaper "El Nacional."
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced the 21st century will be a Latin American
century, for we have done already the democratic and political
corrections, and learned from the mistakes of neo-liberalism and
wrong economic processes," he added.
</P>
<P>
Fox, winner in the July 2 elections, will be in office on
December 1 as Mexico's first president coming from the opposition
in 71 years.
</P>
<P>
The future head of state described Mexico, Brazil, Argentina
and Chile as the "development take-off engines for Latin America."
</P>
<P>
He said his government considers of utmost importance the
rapprochement of Mexico to South America and to the Southern
Common Market (Mercosur).
</P>
<P>
Fox departed Sunday for South America on a trip that will take
him to Chile, Argentina, Brazil and Uruguay, where he will meet
with each country's leader.
</P>
<P>
He made a call for the revitalization of the OAS, "giving it a
great moral authority and a capacity to act that contribute to the
development of our nations."
</P>
<P>
The strengthening of the IDB in "economic and capital terms"
will be a very powerful stabilizing factor for every Latin
American economy, he added.
</P>
<P>
Fox said he will be an "enthusiastic promoter of democracy in
Latin America" and regretted the "slow pace" at which negotiations
are moving for the establishment of the Free Trade Agreement of
the Americas (FTAA) in 2005.
</P>
<P>
Of Mexico, Fox said "we are for globalization" and about the
political conflict in the state of Chiapas, he said he will insist
in resuming negotiations with the rebel Zapatista Army of National
Liberation, which have been stranded for five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
