<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Sets Up New IT Centers in Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) has opened information technology (IT)
centers in four cities of the former Yugoslav republic of
Macedonia, UNDP officials said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The centers are intended to improve the IT skills of youth,
women entrepreneurs, non-governmental organizations (NGOs) and
government officials. Each participant will receive free lessons
in the use of computers, Windows and Window-based applications.
The centers will also offer Internet, E-mail, and web design
training.
</P>
<P>
The centers are located in the four Macedonian cities of
Skopjie, Rostushe, Kriva Palanka and Gostivar, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP will cover the cost of personnel, equipment,
communications and Internet service providers, and will provide
necessary technical assistance. The project is aimed at the
incorporating IT into all aspects of activities related to the
environment, unemployment, youth, gender, business development and
ethnic and social cohesion.
</P>
<P>
"Among the initiative's long term is to prepare Macedonia for
its integration into the European Union," a UNDP press release
said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP, set up in 1965, is the world's largest multilateral
source of grants for sustainable human development. It coordinates
most of the technical assistance provided by the United Nations
system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
