<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Launch Project to Eliminate Food Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government is
to launch a major agricultural project to ensure recurrent food
shortages dogging the country are put to an end once and for all.
</P>
<P>
The planned project, to be undertaken in collaboration with the
World Bank, will focus on boosting productivity in the agriculture
sector, Minister for Agriculture and Cooperatives William Kusila
said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The food situation in the country is not satisfactory, but we
should not lose hope," said the minister in his address at a
public event celebrating the Peasants Day held in the eastern
Morogoro Region.
</P>
<P>
According to Kusila, the project is aimed at encouraging more
farmers to join savings and credit societies that will
recapitalize small scale farmers and enable them to purchase
expensive farm inputs such as fertilizer, pesticide and seeds.
</P>
<P>
He said the government was encouraged by the increase in the
number of credit and saving societies in the country from 728 last
year to 902 this year.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to make a special appeal to more farmers to join
these societies because they are instrumental in eradicating
poverty," Kusila said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that Tanzania is facing a grain deficit of some
662,876 tons in the year 2000/2001 because of a lower-than-
expected harvest in the just ended farming season.
</P>
<P>
Of the 88.6 million hectares of arable land in the eastern
African country, only about half is currently being exploited,
leaving millions of Tanzanians in a constant state of hunger.
</P>
</TEXT>
