<HEADLINE> WFP Reduces Aid Receivers in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP)
office in Angola has cut down the number of people receiving
relief food in the northern province of Malange from 240,000 to
150,000 in order to concentrate its food aid on the most
vulnerable groups in the region.
</P>
<P>
Hans Vikoler, a WFP official in Malange, was quoted on Tuesday
by the official news agency Angop as saying that the decision,
backed by the Malange provincial government, allowed to increase
food ration for each of the most needy person.
</P>
<P>
He added that some 15,000 tons of foodstuffs were delivered
during the first six months of this year to Malange, capital city
of the province, and to the districts of Cacuso and Cangandala.
</P>
<P>
Vikoler said that the WFP's current reserve for the displaced
persons in the province is estimated at some 3,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Hans Vikoler considered as "positive" the WFP's assistance to
the community kitchens as the rate of children with malnutrition
in Malange has shrunk from 36 percent in August of 1999 to the
current 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Malange is one of provinces that suffered most from the 26-year
civil war between the Angolan government troops and the rebels led
by Jonas Savimbi, with most infrastructure destroyed and a large
number of residents displaced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
