<HEADLINE> Ethiopia, Eritrea Urged to Settle on Route for Returning Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The International Committee
of the Red Cross (ICRC) Tuesday urged both Ethiopia and Eritrea to
agree on a common route to let people fleeing a two-year border
conflict between the two countries return home safely.
</P>
<P>
"We urge both governments to agree on a common routing for
future border crossings, and to invite the ICRC again to
participate, so as to continue to monitor the security of all
concerned," the ICRC office in Addis Ababa said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Eritrean authorities reportedly organized the return of 567
Ethiopians at the end of July via the Mereb River, a border river
between Ethiopia and Eritrea, without the knowledge and
involvement of the ICRC.
</P>
<P>
"Among this group were pregnant women, little children and 39
psychiatric patients. These people had to wade through the Mereb
River, and at one point the water was up to their waist," the
statement said, adding some people died during the operations.
</P>
<P>
The ICRC also said that some 2,700 people, mainly women,
children and old people, were sent from a camp 65 kilometers north
of the Eritrean capital of Asmara on Wednesday, dropped off 40
kilometers from the front line, and had to walk for 18 hours
before they reached Ethiopian positions.
</P>
<P>
"These people were exposed to cold, rain, lack of food and
water as well as the danger of minefields," the ICRC statement
said, calling on Eritrea to "cease from this type of operation".
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea, who had been fighting each other over
border disputes since May 1998, signed the Cessation of
Hostilities Agreement on June 18 to end their two-year border
conflict, which has left more than one million people displaced.
</P>
<P>
According to the ICRC, some 10,000 Ethiopians and Eritreans
have returned home since the signing of the ceasefire agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
