<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Wins International Literacy Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Adult Literacy Organization of
Zimbabwe (ALOZ) said on Tuesday that it has won the International
Reading Association Literacy Award with a prize of 15,000 U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
ALOZ was one of the five winners of the international literacy
prize awarded by the United Nations Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization (UNESCO) this year, which also rewards
projects and programs in Bolivia, Iraq, the Philippines and
Senegal.
</P>
<P>
UNESCO said the five prize winners made particularly effective
contributions to the fight against illiteracy, one of UNESCO's
major concerns.
</P>
<P>
The laureates were chosen from 24 nominations submitted by
governments. They would receive their prizes on September 8,
International Literacy Day, in their home countries.
</P>
<P>
ALOZ was rewarded for linking literacy and daily life, namely
the productive and income-generating activities, and for ensuring
that its literacy interventions were conducted in local languages.
</P>
<P>
It sought to involve local public sector officers and education
experts in training the target population groups in project
management. 
