<HEADLINE> Colombian Rebels Reject Clinton's Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's rebel National
Liberation Army (ELN) on Monday rejected the upcoming visit of U.S.
President Bill Clinton to Colombia.
</P>
<P>
ELN's second commander-in-chief Antonio Garcia said, "Clinton
is not welcome because he will not come in a disposition
Colombians have to look for peace. It seems more likely that he
will come with a contrary attitude -- to support military actions.
"
</P>
<P>
Clinton is scheduled to visit the Colombian city of Cartagena
on August 30 to meet his counterpart Andres Pastrana.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said that Clinton will indicate his full
support for the Plan of Colombia, a strategy to fight drug
trafficking, eradicate illegal crops, seek peace with rebel groups,
strengthen democracy and reactivate the world economy.
</P>
<P>
Washington has already announced a 1.3-billion-dollar economic
and military aid package for the Plan.
</P>
<P>
The ELN and the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC)
reject any kind of U.S. assistance, saying it will intensify the
conflict and cause an exodus of coca-leaf peasants to other
Colombian regions and neighboring countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
