<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks End Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks ended higher
Monday in hope that the Federal Reserve would not raise interest
rates any time soon because of the slowing U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 99.26 at 10,867.01,
reaching the highest level in nearly three months. The blue chip
index rose 61.17 points last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The technology heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 75.63 at 3,862.
99, extending its gain of 27.48 points in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor'
s 500 index rose 16.39 at 1,479.32.
</P>
<P>
The market rallied as investors continued to show interest in
technology stocks in hope that the slowing economy would prompt
the Federal Reserve to leave interest rates unchanged at the
August 22 meeting. The central bank has raised rates six times
since last summer in an effort to cool off the economy and keep
inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
About 10 days ago, a report on a stronger-than-expected annual
growth of 5.2 percent in the second quarter ran against a majority
belief that the economy was cooling off after the six rate hikes.
The report hit the stock market after its release.
</P>
<P>
But a stew of the reports, including the July unemployment rate
last week, showed a fresh sign that the economy is slowing. The U.
S. Labor Department reported that the nation's unemployment rate
held steady at 4 percent in July, showing that the tight job
market might be easing a bit.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment report relieved fears of more hikes in rates.
The new data pushed stocks higher last Friday and continued to
drive shares up today.
</P>
<P>
Among the stocks rising today were data networking company
Cisco Systems Inc, computer chip maker Intel Corp., software
company EMC and chip maker Texas Instruments.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 5.73 at 663.52 and the American stock
Exchange index rose 7.49 at 915.46. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies was up 6.26 at 509.87.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange with 1,717 up, 1,156 down and 484
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 850.44 million shares from 943.74
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
