<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ruling Delayed on Northern Irish Parade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Northern Ireland Parades
Commission Monday delayed a ruling on Saturday's proposed march by
the Protestant Apprentice Boys through a nationalist area in
Belfast.
</P>
<P>
The Apprentice Boys want to march along the lower Ormeau Road
before traveling to Northern Irish city of Londonderry, for the
group's annual parade marking the 1689 relief of the city from a
siege by the forces of the Catholic King James II.
</P>
<P>
The commission delayed its decision, which was expected on
Monday, until Wednesday because the body has received further
representations.
</P>
<P>
The commission has also delayed a ruling on the main parade in
Derry, as talks between the Apprentice Boys and the nationalist
Bogside Residents' Group are due to continue on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the commission said: "We have received
representations in the last 24 hours. The position is being very
carefully assessed but there will be no determination before
Wednesday."
</P>
<P>
Nationalist residents of the lower Ormeau Road are objecting to
the loyal order parade going through the area.
</P>
<P>
However, there were scuffles and minor injuries on the Ormeau
Road after nationalists attempted to block the route of the parade.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman for the Lower Ormeau Concerned Community group,
Gerard Rice, said he remained optimistic that this Saturday's
event would be restricted.
</P>
<P>
"We're not surprised the decision was delayed," he said. "But
we would be absolutely shocked and dismayed if the parade was
allowed to go ahead."
</P>
<P>
Talks between the Apprentice Boys and the nationalist Bogside
Residents' Group in Derry have so far failed to reach agreement
over Saturday's parade in the city.
</P>
<P>
The main area of contention involves the so-called feeder
parade along the lower Ormeau Road, where in a ballot last week,
90 percent of residents who voted remained opposed to loyal order
parades.
</P>
<P>
Both the Bogside residents and Apprentice Boys have said they
want to find agreement, but the residents' group has said its
response to the main Apprentice Boys parade in Derry will be
dictated by what happens on the lower Ormeau Road.
</P>
<P>
The Northern Ireland Parades Commission was established in 1997
to determine whether conditions should be placed on contentious
parades in Northern Ireland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
