<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ALADI to Analyze Integration Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Council of Ministers of
the Latin American Integration Association (ALADI) will analyze
the region's integration process in light of world economic
globalization when commemorating the 12th anniversary of the
creation of this organization, ALADI Secretary-General Juan F.
Rojas said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Trade ministers from member countries will hold a meeting here
on August 11, at which Uruguayan President Jorge Batlle will
deliver a speech and final documents will be adopted.
</P>
<P>
He said that Latin America must find new ways to integrate
itself with economic globalization, especially defining new lines
of action for sustainable integration.
</P>
<P>
According to Rojas, economic crisis affecting the world economy
in 1998 had a growing impact on Latin America in 1999 and affected
the integration process in the region.
</P>
<P>
This resulted in a historical fall of 20 percent in inter-
regional trade, less progress in regional trade negotiations and
fewer new free trade accords.
</P>
<P>
Despite these problems, Rojas said, exports of member countries
to the rest of the world in 1999 posted a record high of 253.4
billion dollars, up 21.5 percent over the 1998 level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
