<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Summit Voices Support for Zimbabwean Land Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African
Development Community (SADC) on Monday expressed its full support
for Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe and his controversial land
reform program and urged Britain to provide recourse.
</P>
<P>
"We are convinced that to have a land reform program which is
fair and just to all the stakeholders, it is imperative for the
United Kingdom government to honor its obligations under the
Lancaster House agreement to provide recourse for that purpose,"
said a statement issued at the end of SADC's two-day summit in the
Namibian capital of Windhoek.
</P>
<P>
The statement said SADC leaders had delegated South African
President Thabo Mbeki and Malawian President Bakili Muluzi to make
representations to Britain, Zimbabwe's former colonial ruler, on
behalf of the region.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe said it wants to resettle some 500,000 families on 5
million hectares of land, most of which are white-owned farms
before the rainy season begins in October.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe claimed that the British government reneged on a pledge
to provide funding for the program, as stipulated in the Lancaster
House agreement. This became the central issue in his country's
recent general elections after war veterans occupied white-owned
farms.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting between Mbeki and Mugabe in Zimbabwe last week,
officials said South Africa would help Zimbabwe restore its
battered image and would take steps to stabilize its economy.
</P>
<P>
The SADC heads of state said they were disappointed by the "
partisan and biased manner" in which a sector of the international
media had misrepresented Zimbabwe's land policy.
</P>
<P>
They noted that the policy sought to effect a just and
equitable redistribution of land in a situation where 1 percent of
the population owned over 70 percent of the best arable land.
</P>
<P>
"We reiterate our acceptance of the urgent need to effect land
redistribution in Zimbabwe to address land hunger and poverty
affecting millions of black Zimbabweans," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The SADC leaders said they were greatly concerned about the
Zimbabwe Democracy Act passed by the United States Senate in June,
which it said sought to prescribe to Zimbabwe a land reform and
political dispensation "as prescribed by the U.S. Senate".
</P>
<P>
The statement said the bill sought to authorize the U.S.
president to support opponents of the Zimbabwe government,
including financing propaganda activities against Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"We further note, with concern, that the bill also aims to
subvert Zimbabwe's economic foundation by prohibiting assistance
or debt relief from being extended to Zimbabwe by the U.S. and by
any international financial institutions to which the U.S. is a
member," it said.
</P>
<P>
This punitive piece of legislation was counter-productive and
unjust, and it was regrettable that it was being proposed at a
time when Zimbabwe was involved in a challenging economic recovery
program, and when SADC was trying to deepen the integration
process in the region.
</P>
<P>
"The bill will be a major setback in our community-building
efforts. We therefore urge the U.S. Congress to reconsider its
policy and withdraw the bill before it is passed into law," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said the SADC leaders had directed the foreign ministers
of the SADC troika -- Mozambique, Namibia and Malawi -- plus that
of Zimbabwe, and their ambassadors in Washington, to make
representations to the U.S. congress on SADC's position. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
