<HEADLINE> Britain to Summon Yugoslav Diplomat Over Arrests of Britons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Britain said on Monday that it
would summon the Yugoslav representative in London to demand an
explanation for the detention of two Britons arrested in
Yugoslavia last week.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Office minister Keith Vaz said he was to call the
Yugoslav representative again to require a full explanation.
</P>
<P>
"I shall be calling the head of the Yugoslav interests section
again to see me in London to get a full explanation," Vaz told BBC
radio.
</P>
<P>
Vaz said Britain had not been officially informed of the
charges, or even been formally notified of their detention, after
the two Britons were arrested last week together with two
Canadians.
</P>
<P>
"It's extremely important that the (Yugoslav) regime
understands that we take this issue very seriously indeed," Vaz
said.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav representative was summoned last week shortly
after the men were arrested.
</P>
<P>
Britain said the two Britons are policemen helping to train
police force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav army said on Monday it would bring terrorism
charges against the four detained last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"A criminal case will be launched against two British officers
and two Canadians arrested by the Yugoslav army...since the
investigation so far confirmed they committed the criminal act of
terrorism," a Yugoslav army spokesman reportedly said.
</P>
<P>
Vaz insisted that the men were in Yugoslavia for a holiday.
</P>
<P>
He said Britain would continue to press for "simple, basic
information" from Yugoslav authorities.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia broke off formal diplomatic ties with Britain in
1999 when British aircraft joined NATO bombing raids on Yugoslavia
to force it to withdraw its troops from the province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are represented by "interest sections"
attached to the embassies of other nations in London and Belgrade.
</P>
</TEXT>
