<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Denies Colombian Rebel Presence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The spokesman of the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC), Raul Reyes, has not
officially "entered into Costa Rica," said Costa Rican Foreign
Ministry spokeswoman Vilma Ibarra Monday.
</P>
<P>
There are no entrance records, neither with his war name, nor
with his official name, said the spokeswoman, in reference to a
report coming from Colombia, in which it was said that Reyes would
have traveled to the country last weekend to meet with the
political leader and former Colombian minister, Alvaro Leyva.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry sources said that Leyva himself, who has been
living in Costa Rica since July 1998, would be out of the country
in a couple of months.
</P>
<P>
Leyva has played a key role in peace negotiations in Colombia
and his presence is required quite often as a mediator in the
current peace process taking place in his country, but has kept a
total secret towards the press during this period.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican Foreign Minister Roberto Rojas reiterated that
there is no impediment for Reyes or any other Colombian guerrilla
leader to carry out peace conversations here, as long as it is
with the approval of the Colombian government.
</P>
<P>
Rojas has offered Costa Rica's territory for future
negotiations between government and guerrilla representatives. As
a matter of fact, there is already a meeting on schedule here
between sectors of the Colombian civil society before the end of
the year to analyze the situation in their country. 
</P>
