<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The strike held in the Zimbabwean
capital of Harare by security guards, who are demanding a 150
percent wage increase as well as improved working conditions and
benefits, entered its second day amid several reports of violence
in and around the central Harare.
</P>
<P>
Police Spokesperson Wayne Bvudzijena said the striking security
guards who were moving in large groups had caused extensive damage
to several motor-vehicles in the city center.
</P>
<P>
They overturned a vehicle and damaged several windscreens
during their demonstration which turned violent, said Bvudzijena.
</P>
<P>
He said there had been several reports of guards on duty
abandoning their posts when their colleagues forced them to join
the strike.
</P>
<P>
Police are making investigations on the allegations, he said,
stressing: "It is actually illegal to force someone to join any
industrial action."
</P>
<P>
There was a heavy police presence in the city center. The
police who were in riot gear and armed with baton sticks, shields,
teargas and dogs were monitoring the situation.
</P>
<P>
There are about 110,000 security guards in Zimbabwe. The
security guards in Bulawayo, the country's second largest city,
started the industrial action last Tuesday. 
