<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Calls for Public-Private Sectors Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has called for the enhancement of mutual and beneficial
relationship between the public and private sectors to produce a
conflict-free society, said a press release from the President's
Office on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launching of the Uganda National Hub for Smart
Partnership which took place here Tuesday, Museveni said that all
sections of society, whether public or private, should aim at
innovative and harmonious dialogue to lead to a win-win situation.
</P>
<P>
He noted that those in the public sector need to relate
harmoniously with producers of wealth, adding that investors and
those with entrepreneurial skills should have mutual and
beneficial relationship with those in the public sector.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that smart partnership between countries should
also be at attaining mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
In the spirit of smart partnership, people should be given
information so that they can have hope and know the way forward,
said museveni.
</P>
<P>
The president called for further in-depth discussions with all
stakeholders in development of the country in order to produce a
conflict-free society in which everybody is a winner.
</P>
<P>
At the launching ceremony, Chairman of the Private Sector
Foundation James Mulwana urged all the people to work together to
create wealth, saying that the win-win situation will benefit all
Ugandans.
</P>
<P>
Uganda National for Smart Partnership will enhance the existing
dialogue between government, the private sector, academic, labor,
the media and civil society, said Mulwana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000807.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan Soldiers Return Home From Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- An unspecified number of Rwandan
troops have returned home after withdrawal from Kisangani city in
the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), Rwanda News Agency
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The soldiers who were supposed to take control of Kisangani
city have returned home now that the city is controlled by U.N.
troops," Rwandan army chief of staff Kayumba Nyamwasa said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the rest of over 1,000 Rwandan army in the DRC
will return home as long as Rwanda's security is assured.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that security is the only reason for Rwandan
troops presence in the DRC, adding that Rwanda can not presently
remove all its troops from the DRC because the rebels assisted by
President of the DRC Laurent Kabila have intentions to cause
insecurity in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan and Ugandan troops withdrew from Kisangani last month
after three armed clashes in the city leaving many soldiers and
civilians dead and wounded.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan and Ugandan troops backed rival rebel groups in a two-
year conflict against President Kabila, who is supported by forces
from Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
